ns2:Book01cab066-868d-4d44-aa30-ae02a8b565fb a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Markus Motum" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56785" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This narrative non-fiction recounts the loss at sea of a cargo-container of plastic bath toys, and one little rubber duckie’s adventures: floating among ocean currents, being stuck in the whirling vortex of a massive ocean garbage patch, a lucky release by a passing storm, and washing up on a beach… from where it finally ends up in the bathtub of a child. The storyline includes the worldwide destinations of the duck’s fellow bath toys (Japan, Hawaii, Scotland, U.S. eastern seaboard), as well as the fate of the tons of flotsam that circulates the Earth’s oceans. \r
Stunning illustrations in rich, jewel-like colours recreate the journey of 28,000 plastic ducks slated for delivery to the United States from Hong Kong but that end up “stranded in the middle of the ocean.” \r
The story is told from the perspective of one toy (“We were buffeted by the waves, blown by the wind, and pulled by the ocean currents. We were soon separated and spread out in different directions”), supported by information-rich captions: “A current is a steady movement of water in a particular direction. Ocean currents are driven by tides, wind, and water temperature and density.” These captions are presented in a smaller size type and are visually integrated into the images, encouraging curious readers to follow their text-paths along a horizon line, a current’s flow, and more. \r
One image shows a graphic-style representation of the lost cargo, as if seen form high above: little yellow dots floating in a vast blue wash of calm waters. In one corner, black paint-smudges suggest the clouds of the passing storm. Across the spread, white lines and paint-scrapes skillfully depict the trails of the cargo ship—itself shown as a gorgeous little multicoloured mosaic of shipping containers. In the foreground, a passing seagull (swooping under readers’ eyes) watches the unusual yellow-dot display drifting below. Another spread depicts a world map, with dotted lines showing the lost ducks’ various routes (“Some ducks made their way to Japan. On average, twenty-seven times more plastic winds up in the waters around Japan than anywhere else on the globe.”) Yet another dramatic spread is divided into four scenes of rushing waters – from garbage specked to clear water, from dense black curling waves to crystalline layers of shades of blue. Through each, the vivid yellow duck bobs, sometimes under shadows cast by low skies, sometimes submerged by translucent waters. (“Across weeks, months, and years, the ocean tossed me.”) \r
The storyline offers opportunities for discussion, as well as further research on topics such as ocean and beach conservation around the world, and local recycling plants and processes. Back material provides more details about the ducks, giant ocean garbage patches, facts about plastic and ways to alleviate plastic pollution. Altogether this is a resource that is as informative as it is good-looking.""" ;
    ns2:title "Ducks Overboard! A True Story of Plastic in Our Oceans" ;
