    ns2:publisher ns2:Red_Deer_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This alphabet book is abundant with words, every one relating to a Canadian icon, event or fact. With four words offered for every letter of the alphabet, young readers are sure to find much they recognize in these pages—and much to discover.\r
Words range from the obvious (beaver) to the mysterious (Van Doo), from cultural (Percé) to historic (Voyageur), from inventions (Imax and Insulin) to people (Peterson and Villenueve)—and everything in between. Here is an opportunity to engage readers in identifying the meaning or story behind each word, and in speculating on meanings that are unknown.\r
The illustrations portray fun collections of objects rendered in different styles, depending on the subject. “Wheat, walleye, Wawa, waxwing” depicts a realistic wheat-bundle, a fish-shaped lure, and a souvenir snow-globe stamped with the city’s name. These combine with a two-dimensional graphic of a bird on a berry branch.\r
Dense back material gives outline information on the images and all the selected words that appear. This is likely one of the most complex and sophisticated alphabet books available—useful for a wide range of reading skills.""" ;
    ns2:title "Eh? to Zed: A Canadian Abecedarium" ;
