    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53125" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2003"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“What do you see?” The language of this rhythmic chant invites young readers to join in: a panda bear sees a bald eagle, the bald eagle sees a water buffalo, who sees a spider monkey, and so forth. “Sea Lion, Sea Lion, what do you see?” The earliest readers may wish to peek ahead to the following spread and provide the answer, or they may prefer to sit back and let the words roll: “I see a red wolf sneaking by me.” Rich vocabulary is incorporated into the verbs, as the animals swing, strut, splash and more.\r
Illustrations layer strong textures and colours with simple cut-out forms. They feature recognizable yet graphically represented animals that dominate each dramatic image. Against a sky of vibrant blues, a whooping crane’s black-tipped wings stretch to the corners of the spread. In another, a black panther’s powerful shoulders arc across the page gutter, as its tail almost brushes the top edge.\r
In the end, a child is asked, “what do you see?” The final spread shows the complete menagerie, with their names spelled out, “all wild and free—that’s what I see!”""" ;
    ns2:title "Panda Bear, Panda Bear, What Do You See?" ;
