ns2:Book06523d03-962f-4baf-9ad7-b6958ab974e4 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Sam Maggs" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53168" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This guide for “fangirls” is intended to introduce novices of the genre to the protocols, products and people that make the geek world turn, and to provide connoisseurs with tips and resources they might not have known about. The manual features interviews with high-profile fangirls, a compendium of geek conventions, a list of heroines by genre, a guide to feminist criticism, a how-to for bloggers, plus other geek-able cultural wares. An instructive lexicon provides the etymology of “glomp,” decodes acronyms like “OTP” and helps you get your “squee” on—“the universal noise of the fangirl.”\r
The strong focus on community-building extends off- as well as online, and as this progressive movement first intended, is meant to create space for women in traditionally male-dominated pop-culture fields. The book also includes a list of further resources (for techtalk, beauty products, etc.), and a glossary of “Secret Feminist Code Words, Lingo, and Slang,” including such cryptic terms as misogyny, gender and objectification. Tongue firmly in cheek, this field guide aims to seduce the next generation to an –ism many see as outdated.\r
Written in a conversational first-person point of view sprinkled with exaggerated geekese (“Greetings, nerdlings!”) and monochrome drawings, the manual speaks to readers directly and includes plenty of mantras to remind young women, “You’re mistress of your own domain.”""" ;
