ns2:Book0854044f-e94d-4f65-8c53-b4fbc320a620 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kyo Maclear" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54643" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Born to an aristocratic family, Elsa Schiaparelli was different, even from a young age. Nicknamed “Brutta” she tries planting seeds in her ears, mouth, and nose hoping that flowers will bloom from her face. But her uncle, an astronomer, says that her “moles are as beautiful as the Big Dipper.” As she explores ideas, “the world feels brighter. I am growing into an artist.” \r
\r
The text is poetic, dream-like and written in first person: “Boundless, unstoppable. My fingers itch to combine the strangest materials...I say NO to the expected.” She works with chemist Jean Clément to mix a new shade of pink that is “bright, impossible, impudent, becoming, life-giving, like all the light and the birds and the fish in the world put together.” \r
\r
The mixed media illustrations match Schiaparelli’s creative imagination. One page features a group of her artist friends, including Picasso and Meret Oppenheim. There is no background, and figures appear posed as in fashion drawings, with elongated bodies and tiny heads. Another page shows the first Schiaparelli shop, with a line of aristocrats outside in vibrant patterned clothing: “My unique clothes invite women to express their imaginations fully.” \r
\r
Through her work, Schiaparelli plants “a new seed of beauty” and frees herself from her parents’ harsh judgements. “Beauty itself blooms to reveal the irregular, the imperfect, the smart, tough, goofy, surreal, and wild.” The final page provides additional information about Schiaparelli’s life and accomplishments including the jumpsuit, see-through raincoats, paper clothes and coloured tights.""" ;
