    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Orca ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Fifteen-year-old Meg lives and breathes ballet. When her summer classical dance program is cancelled, her teacher suggests she attend Camp Dance. There, without a ballet option, she ends up joining a contemporary dance group.\r
Told in Meg’s voice, the confessional tone is frank and authentic, drawing readers in to her personal struggles: “The tinted windows reflect my face back at me. I can see worry in my brown eyes, the tightness in my thin lips.” Her secret fear is that she will not make it as a ballerina and her “life feels like a vast hole without ballet.”\r
The authentic use of dialogue and point of view enhance this highly readable story. When Meg ends up in a group choreography with Logan, the girl who dislikes her most at camp, she tries to stay positive: “‘I guess we’re going to dance together,’ I say. ‘Great,’ Logan says sarcastically.”\r
Through a process of confrontation with herself and her peers, she is forced to face her anxieties, discovering that there is more to her identity than ballet. Nio, the choreographer and only friend she has made at camp, explains his dance is about facing fear. At first unable to access emotion or translate it into her body, Meg struggles until Nio helps her let her real feelings grip her: “And then something changes in me. I’m not just dancing steps in the high grass; I’m dancing the feeling in my head, in my heart.”""" ;
