    ns2:datePublished "2009"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Barron's"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Part of the Young Genius series, narrated by an exuberant and scientifically-minded young guide: “this book is about the amazing things on your face called eyes.” We learn quirky and informative facts about the function and biology of the human eye, from how they feel like “squishy grapes” to how they work much like a movie screen. Unusual animal eyes are also explored: fish who see from the sides of their heads to spot predators, and flies who have hundreds of tiny eyes, “that’s why they’re really hard to swat!”
Colourful cartoon illustrations in lively layouts compliment the minimal but informative text. Facts are enclosed in jagged speech bubbles. Our young guide juggles eyeballs, goes to the movies, dissects a model and cries on the couch, all in the name of science. There is a flap to lift on one illustration with a “fish eye view” and some pictorial games at the back demonstrating quirks in how our vision works.
Language is highly accessible, with an inclusive, first-person narrative tone throughout. Subject-specific vocabulary such as iris, pupil, cornea and cone are introduced in engaging ways. “This part is called the lens. It’s like a see-through stretchy plate.” Eye function is related to the everyday world: “Eyelids are a bit like windshield wipers on a car!”
Readers will learn sound scientific facts while having fun reading this humorous, playful book.""" ;
