    ns2:datePublished "2009"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The legend of Robin Hood is presented in this fast-paced action story of revenge, rescue and love. The opening panels show young Robin witnessing his father kill his friend with an arrow to spare the friend from being hanged. Robin is horrified. “If I had a friend in need, I’d be able to save him,” he tells his father. “I will be that good.”\r
The small action-packed panels feature dark illustrations. Faces have thick, black creases, showing determination, rage or fear. Backgrounds are minimal and the palette alters according to setting: light green in Sherwood Forest, dark blue and purple at Nottingham castle. The action is set during the struggles between Richard the Lionheart and his brother, Prince John, adding a layer of tension. The author weaves familiar characters like Maid Marian, Little John and Friar Tuck into the story, each with a strong, unique voice.\r
Robin returns from the crusades to avenge his father’s death but finds the townsfolk in despair due to the corrupt leaders’ heavy taxes. He rallies the other outlaws to fight a moral battle, rerouting money from the rich who pass through Sherwood to the poor, and for payment of Richard’s ransom. Robin Hood flirts with Marian throughout and solicits her help delivering Richard’s ransom. Just as she’s about to be hanged for treason for collaborating with them, Robin severs the rope with his arrow: “I am that good.” Order is restored with the return of King Richard. The final illustration shows Robin and Marian getting married.""" ;
