    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """It’s difficult to imagine readers of any age not being captivated by this book. The language builds slowly with gentle humour, introducing Paul and his goldfish-bowl lifestyle: “Paul used to go around in circles . . . . He made big circles . . . . He circled from left to right . . . and then one day, Bernadette dropped in.”\r
The illustrations are brilliant. Gorgeous compositions of bowl, fish, splash and shadow are rendered in painterly textures that convey character and narrative beautifully. Images and language grow more complex as Bernadette shows Paul the world outside their bowl. Young readers will relish her interpretations. The teapot, pouring into teacups, is an elephant: “She’s not too dangerous. . . . But you must not disturb her when she is feeding her babies.” \r
By the end, Paul’s world has expanded to include towering juice containers, glittering eyeglasses, the glowing orbs of fried eggs and more. Readers of all ages will delight in Bernadette’s ability to infuse joyful, exciting meaning into them all. “Now Paul doesn’t go around in circles anymore. He has something much better to do. Now Paul goes around Bernadette.”""" ;
