    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Quarto"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This introduction to the mysteries and facts surrounding the Stonehenge site offers a lively and scientifically accurate glimpse into this famous site as well as the people of the time. Covering history from 10,000 years ago to the present day, we learn about “Stone Age Britain,” “The First Farmers,” how land ditches were dug, and rituals around gods, planting, harvest and slaughter. We discover the methods used to haul enormous rock formations over 250 km and the Stone Age technology needed to install them. \r
Rich, informative language and succinct text keep readers engaged: “Domesticated pigs and goats were the first ‘farm machines,’ eating tough wild plants and rooting up undergrowth.” \r
Watercolour and colour pencil illustrations in cool tones have a loose, freehand feel. Neolithic and Mesolithic people are depicted in their environments on both land and water. Speech bubbles for cavemen and women add a personal, almost contemporary touch. Sidebars in subdued colours with sketches of implements, boats and site plans provide more information. A glossary at the back defines specific vocabulary like: Ferriby boat, lintel and trilithon.\r
While Stonehenge is still shrouded in mystery, this up-to-date resource is an exciting starting point for exploration.""" ;
    ns2:title "Secrets of Stonehenge" ;
