ns2:Book11827a08-95ba-4034-b765-8ca8c87d778e a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Joseph Marshall" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54202" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Abrams"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Jimmy is three parts Lakota and one part white, but he has blue eyes and light brown hair. This is one of the reasons two bullies at school tease him relentlessly. He takes refuge in nature: “The trees accepted him just the way he was, blue eyes and all.” When Jimmy’s grandpa learns of the teasing, he decides to take Jimmy on a trip to visit the historical sites where battles were waged against the Long Knives (European settlers). The focus is on Crazy Horse, the “greatest Lakota warrior.” He, like Jimmy, had light brown hair.\r
\r
Jimmy’s grandpa is a gifted storyteller and the book toggles between the stories he tells and the conversations he has with Jimmy about the content of the stories. “Why did they attack our people?” Jimmy asks after his grandpa tells him the first story that involves the Long Knives burning a Lakota village and killing the residents in 1855. The answer is not simple, and Grandpa Nyles wisely takes his time during their trip to explain the context in which the events occurred.\r
\r
There is no avoiding the violence and trauma in these historical events, but with Grandpa Nyles as the guide, the reader receives this painful history without bitterness and anger. There is sadness sometimes. “That’s the sad part about war and battles,” he tells Jimmy. “Doesn’t matter who you are, what side you’re on. It’s still sad, no matter what kind of uniform you wear or the colour of your skin.”\r
\r
This sensitive novel honours the history of the Lakota people and other First Nation tribes, as well as the incredible bravery and generosity displayed by Crazy Horse. When Jimmy returns to school, he has a newfound confidence that his bullies sense immediately.\r
.""" ;
