    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Dial Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A tender representation of the heart, which at times can be “a window” and at others “a slide.” The fluctuations of the heart are accompanied by striking illustrations done using monotype printmaking and feature a palette of black and white with yellow. One two-page spread shows a child bending down to pick a small yellow heart-shaped flower. The sky and ground are textured light grey and black with faint hints of yellow, while the text reads: “Some days it is tiny.” The following page reads, “but tiny can grow . . .” and shows another child gazing up at a blossoming tree with large yellow flowers that appear to glow in contrast with the dark background. The story acknowledges hardships: “There are days it is broken . . .” A child is shown holding up a broken vase to her mother. The background is yellow and the people are drawn in dark grey and black. The following page shows the vase glued back together and holding yellow flowers: “but broken can mend, and a heart that is closed can still open again.” On the opposite page, a child is opening the blinds while yellow light pours in. \r
\r
The gentle, poetic text takes us through the ups and downs of the heart before concluding, “My heart is a shadow, a light, and a guide. Closed or open . . . I get to decide.” The final illustration shows a child with open arms against a glowing yellow backdrop with blooming heart flowers.""" ;
