ns2:Book12cc9791-0a53-4d8b-a5a6-17188e87e41a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Ben Lerwill" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54927" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Atheneum"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This fascinating collection of stories about the lives and heroic acts of creatures around the world offers fully illustrated profiles on courage, intelligence, loyalty, sacrifice and more. Double-page spreads focus on famous animals such as Winnie the bear and Jumbo the elephant, and lesser-known ones, like Ozy the octopus who could open a jar in seconds and Winter the dolphin with a special tai Hand-painted illustrations provide a storybook setting for these true-life tales, supported by historic photos of the animals and their humans. \r
“Clearly animals know more than we think, and think a great deal more than we know.” Through this engaging and accessible collection of stories about these animals’ lives, with 50 illustrated spreads that recount eye-opening acts of heroism and service, the book allows insight into the lives of our fellow creatures. \r
The table of contents allows for quick access to each animal’s profile and is divided into five sections: “Rescue & Protect” “Adventure & Explore” Change & Solve” “Discover & Pioneer” and “Inspire & Influence”. Clear language is conversational “It was a warm August day in 1996 when Bintu Jua suddenly had a very unexpected visitor ….” with frequent subheadings to engage browsing readers: “ESCAPE FROM THE FLAMES. It was incredibly dangerous, both for the people who lived close by and the many different animals that lived in the woodland ….” \r
The profiles provides portraits of determination: “She arrived blinded in one eye and coated in blood, but her message was still dangling from her wounded leg,” sacrifice: “We don’t know exactly how long she lived on her extraordinary mission high above Earth,” and caring: “His last words before he died were to Irene… As she opened the door to go and wished him good night, he said, ‘You be good. I love you.’” Altogether, these stories present excellent opportunities for thought and discussion on relationships with our fellow creatures, and one another. \r
Simple illustrations use warm colours and painted markings to create a storybook setting for each animal’s tale. One image shows same-sex penguin pair, Roy and Silo: one is offering his partner a fish, as the other protects their adopted egg between his feet. Another depicts “Streetcat Bob” curled around the shoulders of his street musician friend, James. Sidebars include quotes from the humans involved in each animal’s story. End material includes a world map, showing each animal’s birthplace, along with a glossary and index.""" ;
    ns2:title "WildLives: 50 Extraordinary Animals that Made History" ;
