ns2:Book160d93d9-f47a-4169-9ea4-b8141a97c40d a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Nancy Loewen" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53744" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Capstone"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Prometheus, as the Greek myth goes, angered Zeus by giving fire to humans. In revenge, Zeus created Pandora to wreak havoc on humankind. He fashioned a young woman and introduced her to Epimetheus, Prometheus’ brother. As a wedding gift, Zeus gave the couple a large vase—but, he admonished, they were not to open it. Pandora, who is not naturally curious in this version, cautions her husband: “Do you think he’s up to something?” While Pandora can resist the temptation to open the vase, curiosity is another matter entirely for Epimetheus’ cat, Cuddles. Sure enough, as soon as the naughty feline gets half a chance, there goes the vase and out come hunger, disease, old age and war.\r
Narrated in an easy, contemporary vernacular, this light-hearted take on the myth of Pandora dwells on her creation and perfection, straying considerably from conventional versions—which tend to omit the existence of “Cuddles.” A preface, a brief list of suggested reading and a glossary round out the pedagogical aspects, while a “Critical Thinking” section asks readers to weigh in on Pandora’s revisions. The first-person narration has a light tone and is accompanied by vibrant cartoonish illustrations.\r
The mythological explanation for all the worst human woes, it seems, may have been nothing more than a sleight of paw.""" ;
    ns2:title "Pandora Tells All: Not the Curious Kind" ;
