    ns2:datePublished "1992"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This historical perspective opens on the Ice Age 20 000 years ago and chronicles Canada’s development until the oil-tanker spills in British Columbia and the Syrian refugee arrivals of 2016, providing a long preface to the 2017 celebration of the 150th anniversary of Confederation. Chapters touch on the territory’s geological past, briefly discuss pre-contact populations, and provide broad treatments of Canada’s colonial, military, technological, athletic and cultural history. From the Gold Rush to war brides to Farley Mowat, no stone is left unturned from sea to sea. Many asides lighten the informative text with bits of amusing trivia: camels were once imported as pack animals to the interior of British Columbia, albeit unsuccessfully, as “some of the camels escaped and went wild, but they could not survive the winters.”\r
The extensive text is clearly written; the well-delineated sections allow browsing or more linear reading. Boxed insets feature smaller write-ups of individual events, such as the 1972 “greatest goal” scored by Canadian Paul Henderson against the Soviets. The book includes maps (First-Nation groups and trading patterns), many colour drawings (of the British attack on Montcalm’s men, of the Chasse-galerie legend), reproductions of iconic Canadian art (Krieghoff) and photographs of historic moments (Pierre Trudeau looking on as Queen Elizabeth signs the British North America Act).\r
This comprehensive resource reviews the many moments and events that have shaped Canada, past and present.""" ;
