    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Vibrant watercolour illustrations invite the reader to linger over the landscapes to discover the “treasures hiding in the trees and on the ground and in the air.” Each page introduces a different bird species and indicates how many are hidden: “On a beautiful morning you might just find ten black-capped chickadees perching in the trees.” The accompanying two-page spread shows two lush trees with chickadees slightly camouflaged among the boughs and leaves. On another page, six robins appear within the branches of a spruce tree along with butterflies, ferns and glorious light pink flowers.\r
\r
The text is short and playful as it indicates which bird species is hidden: “As a few raindrops fall, you just might find seven wrens singing.” Each page is linked with the previous one, highlighting the interconnectedness of species: “While the wrens take cover, you might just find six robins looking for worms.” The illustrations are delicate, with light greens, pinks and blues. The use of collage adds depth, definition and texture. The final illustration is executed almost entirely in shades of green and features a chickadee, a hummingbird and two warblers feeding their young among the pale leaves. \r
\r
A final page offers bird-watching tips and additional information about the species that have been introduced.""" ;
