    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This attractive little pull-the-flap book uses simple phrases and bold illustrations to differentiate between tall, high and up in three humorous short stories for very early readers. Through rhythmic dialogue, the language encourages beginners, as does the large expressive type in speech balloons: “‘I cannot go high!’ ‘Why?’ Because I cannot fly!’”\r
Quirky characters in minimal settings are created with strong line and bright, flat colour—for an effect that’s both cartoon-like and graphic. Youngsters will enjoy lifting the flaps among these sturdy pages. When a big bird joins a small one in a spindly tree (“Now I am up, too!”), the flap reveals unexpected and calamitous results: a snapped tree and two stunned birds. (“You should have stayed down!”). \r
There is ample opportunity for discussion about opposites and comparatives. Children may be encouraged to tell or draw their own stories, based on these ideas.""" ;
