    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A young boy has to talk about a family member for show-and-tell, but the only person he can come up with is his granddad, Frank, an old curmudgeon who “doesn't like noise, or today's music, or gadgets and gizmos (or new things), or—” How will he possibly be able to compete with all the fun people his classmates have lined up for their presentation? The funny thing is, Frank ends up surprising him—and the class—with a slew of exciting war stories from his past.\r
Stylized, cartoonish illustrations that combine digital and hand-drawn elements with collage and a hint of charcoal produce scenes that are both detailed and evocative. At the beginning of the story, Frank is portrayed in dark, greyish tones that later give way to a more colourful rendering, mirroring the boy's altered perception of him. Visual cues (e.g. italics, boldface type, changes in font size) draw attention to particular words and phrases that describe the emotions of the narrator. Humorous and offbeat, this heart-warming story reminds children that family members—even seemingly boring ones—are people with real human stories.""" ;
