    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Fun rhymes, good pacing and clever vocabulary make this lengthy poem a joy to read aloud. Featuring two fascinating characters, it conveys a story of loneliness, shed as friendship is found.\r
The language revels in detailed character descriptions of both the wizard (“His bundle is bulgingWith rabbits and string,And a sort of machineThat he’s teaching to sing”) and the castle-dwelling cat (“And every dayAt half past fourShe sets the tableFor twelve or more.”)\r
Whimsical illustrations seem to vibrate with sketchy line and soft watercolour effects. The scruffy, hobo-like wizard plods through contemporary landscapes. In one of these images, Toronto’s Casa Loma pokes through the skyline. Other images depict the elegant cat living in grandeur inside the castle—showing that loneliness lurks in all strata of society.\r
When the two characters meet, words and images celebrate the joys of companionship: sharing a meal, a fireside chat and an amazing array of wizard-magic. “if some dayyou chance to lightOn Casa LomaLate at night,Go up to the window,Peek inside,And then you’ll seeI haven’t lied.”""" ;
