    ns2:datePublished "2006"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Sometimes, “sorry” is not enough. A young boy named Jack makes friends with Charlie, the school bully. Before he fell in with this new companion, Jack felt like “a nobody.” But being pals with someone who does not respect his classmates and tries to get away with hurtful behaviour proves unsatisfying. When the two boys wreck their fellow student’s science project, a teacher steps in and asks them to do something that shows true remorse. Jack learns what a true apology is and chooses to find friends who are more considerate.\r
Easy to relate to, the realistic story is told from Jack’s point of view. Dialogue is vivid and truthful, depicting a young person’s thoughts and feelings with authenticity. Jack’s voice is full of the colloquialisms and laidback language of youth: “I lucked into being his friend when I rescued Charlie’s Frisbee from Mr. Finkelstein’s roof. Charlie thought it was pretty cool that I didn’t get caught.”\r
Created with a digital pen, the bright, colourful illustrations have the warmth and texture of acrylics. Visuals focus on human situations, emotions and actions. Charlie’s look of bewilderment dominates the page when a teacher stands up to the lack of sincerity in his apology.\r
Resources at the back give background information on what an apology consists of, dos and don’ts, and questions for discussion.""" ;
