    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Enchanted Lion Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This excellent book offers a penetrating and tender look at death and loss. A subtle mood of suspense and foreboding is set from the start. Stringent language invites readers into the setting, while hinting that something is missing: “My dad isn't listening to the radio. He’s sitting in the living room, where the only sound is the crackling of the fire.” Confident readers will rush through the first pages to learn what’s happened to this small family.\r
Photos of paper cut-out scenes provide the illustrations, playing with the flat effect of paper in a three dimensional setting. The colours are sombre, with the odd highlight in red paper, aptly conveying this uniquely Scandinavian setting.\r
Both sleepless and sad, father and son embark on a late-night tramp through the woods. The boy frets about food for the birds; he frets about the fox. They wish on a shooting star. Like the wishes that must be kept secret, this story is as skilful in it what it doesn't say, as in what it describes. And on their return, even though nothing has changed, the shadowy house now glows with a warm light. Young readers who've experienced the loss of a loved one, and those who haven’t, will take comfort in the story’s conclusion: “‘Everything will be all right,’ says Daddy . . . ‘I’m sure.’”""" ;
