    ns2:datePublished "1990"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This re-telling of an ancient Chinese folktale transports readers back to the reign of Emperor Ch’in Shih Huang. The story follows seven extraordinary brothers, each with a special power. One has unbreakable bones; another is resistant to heat. The youngest brother, however, sheds tears that can drown a village, so his older brothers do everything they can to keep him from crying. To that end, one brother tries to alleviate the suffering of those he finds labouring to construct the Great Wall of China. The jealous emperor decides to execute that brother for his exceptional strength. But the brothers, who look almost identical, cleverly switch places and use their combined powers to escape execution.\r
Longer text successfully captures the flavour of long ago and far away: “Third brother . . . could walk across China in a straight line, lifting up any mountains that got in his way and carefully putting them back behind him.”\r
Watercolour illustrations bring the mountainous and misty landscape of rural China to life; unique details – billowing flag standards, softly folding robes – add to the ambiance. \r
The brothers in this classic tale are resourceful heroes who demonstrate the strong bond that can exist between siblings.""" ;
