    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Text is minimal and poetic, laid out in a lovely font with a handwritten style. Emotions are beautifully articulated using spare language: “Now time passes slowly, and the emptiness follows Maia everywhere she goes. It’s boring. She can’t play with it, and it won’t let other children near.” \r
\r
Digitally enhanced illustrations in a palette of browns, beiges and teal blues feature the children as the central, fleshed-out elements of layouts. An outline of suitcases, the bare bones of a telescope and the circle of darkness for the night sky enhance feelings of emptiness, whereas a flourish of colour and exotic animals conveyed across telephone wires brings joy back in. \r
\r
The pairing of text with whimsical and delicate graphic elements leads to a beautifully balanced story about mixed feelings and holding onto the things we love. \r
\r
When the two friends are reunited, they find that some things never change.""" ;
