    ns2:datePublished "1991"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This anthology of amusing, lighthearted verse shines a light on universal experiences of childhood: being naughty, digging a hole to a distant land, tracking down the perfect pet. Lee’s wacky, off-the-wall humour puts a twist on a familiar subject and then wraps it in delectable, mouth-watering diction. This is a world where polliwogs “do the wobble-wobble” and kids rush “lickety-split” to the corner store for candy.
Rhyme, alliteration and word play will delight the ear, eye and mind. The introductory title poem sets the tone of the book and awakens readers to the riches of diversity, reminding them that kids are like the cones in an ice cream store, where “there’s chocolate, and vanilla,/And there’s maple and there’s more./And there’s butterscotch and orange—/Yes, there’s flavours by the score.”
Endearing old-fashioned paintings capture the sly tone and inventive worlds described in the poetry. Detailed artwork uses a muted, earthy palette.
First published in 1991, the glut of nonsense words and fun phrases (e.g. “razzmatazz,” “skinny marinka dinka dine”) in this modern classic could inspire dramatic choral readings.""" ;
