ns2:Book22887335-b81b-43e3-9cbd-7d6ce5985945 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Emily Lindin" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54249" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Zest Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This intimate diary, written in the 1990s by an actual middle school girl, is transcribed with footnotes by her grown-up self. While most entries are preoccupied with oscillating friendships and relationships, school dances and parties, it also centres on sexuality and bullying—Emily is labelled a “slut” by her peers after her boyfriend briefly puts his hand down her pants.\r
The adult Emily’s footnotes provide context and insight: “When I acted on my sexual curiosity, I was labelled as a ’slut.’ When I held back for fear of the ‘slut’ label, I was accused of being a ‘tease’””.\r
Bullying also takes a cyber form. A classmate, whose screen name is “DieEmilyLindin,” writes: “Why haven’t you killed yourself yet, you stupid slut?” At the height of her emotional pain, Emily engages in cutting, which adult Emily explains was “an impulsive, physical reaction to the sadness I was feeling in that moment.”\r
Emily’s entries are detailed and revealing, even about her own cruelty: “Stacy giggled and said, ‘Well, life sucks and then you die.’ I looked up. ‘Only for you, Stacy.’ She stopped giggling. That had been my goal. … I hate it when she giggles.”\r
The diary provides an unflinching look at the socialization and sexualization of girls at this age and the negative impacts of bullying, as well as the process of resolution. Through it all, we hear Emily’s authentic middle school voice, tempered and illuminated by her adult commentary and the insight and healing she has achieved since.""" ;
