ns2:Book23da848b-a040-4206-a051-1e824455692a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "James Marshall" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54136" ;
    ns2:datePublished "1987"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Red Riding Hood, as is known, is “kind and considerate,” so when her mother asks her to take a custard to her ailing grandmother, she jumps at the chance: “She loved going to Granny’s—even though it meant crossing the deep, dark woods.” Despite her mother’s exhortation not to speak to strangers, she allows a wolf to escort her; after all, as the wolf says, “you never know what might be lurking about.” While the girl dawdles, the wolf goes on ahead to Grandmother’s, and the rest is history. \r
\r
The author keeps many of the traditional repetitions—“what big teeth you have” and so on—but adds a more contemporary tone to the characters and dialogue. So, for instance, when Granny asks who is at the door, the wolf replies, “‘It is I, your delicious—er—darling granddaughter.’” Granny, notably, has something of an attitude: when the wolf barges in, she’s annoyed at “having her reading interrupted” and her gratitude for their rescue is partly because it was so dark inside the wolf that “I couldn’t read a word.”\r
\r
The colourful, full-page, cartoon-style images provide a literal visual rendering of the narrative, with amusing details (for instance, when the wolf approaches the grandmother’s house, only her feet are seen poking out of the blankets; when Red Riding Hood comes along, she has the same perspective, but with the wolf’s furry grey paws). The final humorous image shows Red Riding Hood vowing to never speak to strangers again, wisely shunning a dissolute-looking alligator.""" ;
    ns2:title "Red Riding Hood" ;
    ns1:isCoupDeCoeur false ;
