    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Candlewick Studio"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The simple text and artful illustrations of this picture book offer a gentle reminder of the importance of trees. This short text presents facts about trees to young readers by using familiar tropes such as opposition—“Trees sleep in winter and wake up in spring”—and accessible figurative language—“Trees have their heads in the clouds and their feet on the ground.” The book covers growth and dormancy as well as more complex behaviours such as mycorrhizal networks, and it touches on the ecosystemic importance of trees for humans and other animals. The short sentences are broken up over several pages, paced with the slow growth of the book’s subject. “Trees,” the book concludes, “are marvellous beings.” \r
\r
The two-page colour spreads use shapes and textures to breathe visual life into trees and plants of all kinds: stamps and swirls extend the foliage of an apple tree, for instance, while heart-shaped red flowers dot a meadow that unfurls beneath different shapes and sizes of trees. Some trees’ foliage is rendered in spongy dark green circles, while the individual leaves in a tree that is home to several nesting birds are more detailed, in shades of green, turquoise and blue. The mixed-media illustrations convey a sense of play while evoking the intricacies of the natural world.""" ;
    ns2:title "Trees" ;
