    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This is a charming tale about being the smallest: “At home, Daddy, Mommy, Nicholas and Marie are all taller than me. So is Gus, our dog.” A watercolour illustration shows a closeup of a recent family portrait that features the family standing in a line, the mother’s hand resting on her pregnant belly. Mimi is shown on the far right beside their big brown dog.\r
Each page shows Mimi’s struggle, from trying to navigate the busy sidewalks (“I wouldn’t be surprised if nobody noticed me”) to riding the school bus (“I bounce all over the place on the way to school.”) She wonders: “When will I grow big enough to take up as much space in the world as everyone else?”\r
Simple, elegant watercolours accompany the gentle text. The colours are soft, the details minimal, just enough to illustrate Mimi’s predicament. One page shows Mimi in the classroom, trying to write on the blackboard, where she can only reach the very bottom. The opposite page shows Mimi getting served lunch first in a long line-up of kids, which her friend Remy explains is one of the good things about being small. Once she starts thinking about it, Mimi realizes there “are some advantages to being small . . . like snuggling between Mommy and Daddy.” When she meets her baby brother for the first time, not only is Mimi no longer the smallest, she offers him advice: “Just be patient. One day you’ll be big too.”""" ;
