    ns2:publisher "Tuttle"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Thank you! I had a great night! I will visit you again in the museum.” A souvenir figurine sparks magical dreams in this tale of one child’s discovery of the Qin Shihuang Mausoleum in northwest China. The story offers historic context, “army was created to follow the first emperor of China into the afterlife,” and is enriched with captions that convey impressive details, “No two faces looked exactly the same … some experts think that real soldiers served as models.”
Illustrations in brush and ink effects combine the whimsy of dream-life with accuracy in the figures, their equipment, the animals and the site in which they were found. In one spread, Ming rides with the General in a bronze horse-drawn chariot across blue-wash skies. The next shows him waving goodbye in his own yard, the General and his chargers now wisp-like brushstrokes, galloping into the distance.
Through both language and image, this book encourages imaginative engagement with past cultures, making it a fine addition to any library of history and archaeology.""" ;
