ns2:Book2931ee29-61ea-4055-92e1-909762efdc30 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andrew Larsen" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54300" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """It’s the end of grade five and everything in Henry’s life seems to be suddenly different. Henry thinks “it sucks that things have to change”: first his little brother was born, then his parents decided that his mother would go back to work while his father stayed home, and now his best friend Max is spending more time with his chess-club friends than with him. Henry tries to make sense of this new world order, even as he becomes increasingly aware of economic, social and interpersonal nuances: Henry’s family doesn’t have very much money, and for the first time he’s embarrassed to wear Max’s second-hand clothes, or the brand knock-offs his father buys; and he finds that his mother is better at giving emotional advice, especially as Max becomes increasingly close to his new friends and begins to make fun of Henry. As he grows up, Henry finds that he’s expected to be more responsible—something he learns the hard way when he loses his grandfather’s dog. \r
Henry’s first-person voice is believably concerned with camp, comic books and the weirdness of looming puberty (“I hope it never happens to me,” Henry gripes), and his underlying emotional insight shows the beginning of a more mature consciousness. The secondary characters are well-hewn accessories to Henry’s coming of age, from his precociously verbal baby brother Sam, to Max, to his parents and grandparents, and to Gretchen, a schoolmate who runs a dog-walking business and who Henry starts bumping into an awful lot. The preadolescent concerns—“I love my mom but there’s a certain way to talk to your kid in public,” Henry protests when she refers to herself as his “Mommy” — as well as short sentences, an accessible narrative, and devices such as reproduced lists and emails round out the sense of Henry as he comes to terms with the changes he is facing.""" ;
