ns2:Book2c88a9ad-8f3f-4f33-a828-4448c6018978 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Aga Maksimowska" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54910" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Pedlar Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Gosia—short for Małgorzata—is only eleven, but her body is already that of a woman. She feels physically awkward, and the impression of being out of place is only exacerbated when her mother, who has been away in Toronto for over two years, finally brings over her daughters from Poland. Gosia doesn’t speak English, can’t stand her mother’s boyfriend, looks after her little sister Kasia resentfully, and misses her Babcia and Dziadek, especially her grandmother, who looked after her during the long months of her mother’s absence. We follow Gosia as she comes of age—her first bra, which she hides behind the toilet; her first period, which arrives on an outing to the beach with her semi‑estranged father; her grandfather’s Alzheimer’s; her grandmother’s death and her first visit back to Gdànsk, where she feels like “a foreigner, a floater.” In the maelstrom of adolescence, torn between her past and her future, Gosia struggles to hold on to what she knows and who she is. “Everything is changing,” she fears, “while my memories stay untouched.” \r
Narrated in a candid and often cheeky first person, the novel chronicles the unwavering push of several strong women into the inevitable future, tracing as it does the Autumn of Nations uprisings in Eastern Europe and the last days of the Soviet Union. Gosia’s physical girth, stature and precocity are a complex metaphor for displacement and belonging. “After Babcia is gone,” she notes, “my root system is completely severed and my body makes straight for the skies in an attempt to be with her.” The story is replete with cultural oddities—a carp awaits its plated fate in the bathtub, black-market goods are common currency—but the voice of the main character, although she feels perpetually “somewhere in between,” anchors the story, on both sides of the Atlantic.""" ;
