ns2:Book2ee589b7-5c42-4158-b576-019adc05a5aa a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Elizabeth MacLeod" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53340" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Canada, this history muses, is “a place where people have come to make their homes,” where they have shaped its defining events. From the first organized game of indoor hockey in 1875 to the production of the Canadarm, many of the figures and moments are iconic. The book includes seminal feminist moments as well as the history of the First Nations. It also includes some of the sociological touchstones for which Canada has become known, like its relatively early legalization of same-sex marriage and its open attitude to immigration. Darker times in Canadian history are touched on, notably the destruction of Africville and the legacy of residential schools. An appended handful of “Great Canadians” introduces readers to other nationally significant figures such as Louise Arbour and Arthur Currie.\r
Appealing, cartoonish spot colour drawings represent moments and figures with simplicity: Rick Hansen smiles from his wheelchair, Marc Garneau floats in zero gravity, Lucy Maud Montgomery poses in front of Green Gables. \r
The heavier text of this reference is broken into smaller, dated sections on each page: “1871 Irish immigration” is followed by “1872 British home children.” Back matter includes a comprehensive index.\r
Here you will find many of the places and people that have made Canada “something to celebrate.”""" ;
    ns2:title "Canada Year by Year" ;
