ns2:Book3163cdc6-90e0-496d-939e-c8f206eaaf81 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Linda Sue Park" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56643" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Clarion Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A middle-gradelate elementary class is given an unusual homework assignment: if there was a fire in your home, what is the one thing you would save? (People and pets are in no danger.) As the students give brief oral reports on their choices and reasoning, their individual characters, values and home situations are revealed. Sometimes the reports inspire dissent among the students, at other times, support. Their stories connect and interweave; the teacher contributes her own ‘homework’. By the end, a mood of increased intimacy, mutuality and friendship prevails among the class. \r
“Your Most Important Thing. Any size. A grand piano? Fine.” This fully-illustrated, short volume of prose poems offers readers an array of child characters, their values and unique voices: “My sketchbook . . . I could draw the fire, ‘cause I’ve already drawn, like a million flames,” “If a fire burns everything up, you’re gonna need money. A lot. Am I the only one here with any smarts? MY DAD’S WALLET. DUH” \r
\r
Some children know right away what they’d save (“Promise you won’t think it’s stupid?”); others are at a loss (“heck, my Neil DeGrasse Tyson books, seven all by themselves! . . . every one of them is awesome”). The monologues—and occasional dialogue—reveal a variety of interests (“Did Mae Jemison start like this? Or Ellen Ochoa? We proved that the dirt on the streets around here holds chips and flakes from real stars”) and socioeconomic backgrounds: “I’d walk out with nothing. Not a dang thing. Come see it for your own self, place is a total dump . . . be glad to see it burn down.” \r
Evocative monochrome illustrations use pencil and wash effects to create spot images and full-spread background settings to complement the sparse language. These charming pictures combine a naïve sensibility with a sophisticated deployment of light, shadow and graphic-style line. The introductory spread shows the school and its paved courtyard (complete with a basketball net). The building façade is suggested by a minimalist array of pencil-sketched boxes, hanging in white space. In contrast, the busy city background uses a full palette of gray tones, white and black, to portray high rises, rooftop water towers and a passing train. Many images play with artful transparency. In one scene, a bedside lamp is represented with a loosely painted outline, while the bed, floorboards and a cast shadow are represented according to visual norms. A double-page spread depicts a Latin American feast (including corn, chiles, leaf-wrapped tamales), while pencil-rendered, serving-spoon outlines lean against densely painted pots of soup and beans. \r
\r
Altogether, this attractive and engaging book offers opportunities to discuss personal values and literary craft. It is also a fine model for the readers’ own creative projects, whether oral, written or visual—or a combination of all three. An author’s note discusses the form of sijo poetry, on which these prose-poems were loosely based.""" ;
