ns2:Book3205de60-2839-4459-9b0f-1a20fdb8c34a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Gordon Lightfoot" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53515" ;
    ns2:datePublished "1967"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In 1967, Gordon Lightfoot was commissioned by the CBC to write a song for Canada’s centennial. The resulting lyrics are accompanied here by gorgeous, evocative illustrations that fill the oversized pages. The blood and sweat it took to build “an iron road running from the sea to the sea” is celebrated and honoured through images of Canadian geography, First Nations peoples and the “navvies,” predominantly Chinese immigrants who built the railway\r
Lightfoot’s lyrics are a combination of revelling in the forward-looking dreams of John A. Macdonald who unified a nation, and a quiet honouring of the land and people who came before and who were forever changed by the railway. “There was a time in this fair land when the railroad did not run,When the wild majestic mountains stood alone against the sun.”\r
The dominating double-page chalk pastel spreads are an extraordinary compliment to the text. Breathtaking in their scope and captivating in their visual detail, they depict panoramas of landscapes from the Rockies to the Gaspé, including incredible historic details and commentary in their composition. In one image, a buffalo confronts a steam engine that is puffing smoke in the shape of the map of Canada.\r
End matter for this nuanced piece of Canadian history includes the music and song lyrics, a key to the images with thumbnails, a brief history of the railway, as well as further reading.""" ;
    ns2:title "Canadian Railroad Trilogy" ;
