    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """That’s how the basketball bounces: from the point of view of the fans, the players and even the ball, readers learn about one of the world’s most popular sports. The integration of facts into this series of poems is seamless and playful. For example, when James Naismith was first inspired to hang fruit baskets for his students to toss balls into, “They all agreed—but said, ‘We bettertake the peaches out!’”\r
Written mostly in metered rhyming verse (there are also a few free-verse examples), these poems are percussive and accessible, each one hinging on some aspect of the sport, from the maple floors of basketball courts to the determination of a young girl who “trained her fingertipsfor weeks and weeks and weeks” until—“who knew? It’s truethat strengtheningyour fingers on the ballmakes every other part of youget stronger overall.”\r
The abundant colour spot illustrations offer cartoonish counterpoints to the thematic content: a poem about the science of bouncing is portrayed by a lab full of balls, while a poem about height has a little boy standing before his much taller shadow. An accompanying website offers even more basketball poems and invites readers to write their own.""" ;
