ns2:Book3ca73cc6-5610-4a7a-8c36-d8253eac2a67 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Laurence Pringle" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56323" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Boyds Mills Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Storytelling language recounts a year in the life of a vixen—hunting, hiding, meetings with her mate and raising a litter of kits—with lush illustrations and extensive back material providing further fascinating information about the red fox. \r
\r
Realistic, expressive paintings beautifully support the intimate perspective of this non-fiction narrative: “Vixen stands and stretches. She looks and listens all around. She sniffs the air… Feeling hungry, Vixen sets off on a hunt.” \r
\r
Painterly illustrations depict thick fur, expressive eyes, snowy days, a cozy underground den and scenes of fox family life. One entertaining spread shows a winter hunt (“Hidden beneath a foot of snow, a meadow mouse chews on grasses. It makes tiny sounds: nibble, nibble, nibble”). Vixen stalks, springs higher than the length of her own body, and lands with her forelegs and sharp face buried in snow—her bushy tail and back legs still high in the air. Another spread shows a warming landscape, softened by the rosy tones of dawn or dusk. Vixen’s head pops out from a hole in the ground as her mate brings food (“mice, chipmunks, and any other prey he caught”). \r
\r
Facts about foxes (“Vixen visits some abandoned animal burrows. With her front feet she clears dead leaves from the entrance of each one. She crawls underground to investigate”) are skillfully woven into the tale: “Vixen especially likes one burrow on a sunny hillside with scattered trees. It has two entrances, like a front and back door.” Throughout the story there is much opportunity for speculation and discussion. Key vocabulary, presented in italics, is explained in the text and may also be found in the book’s glossary: “Foxes are omnivores, which means they eat both animal and plant food. But in winter Vixen finds no berries or other plant foods to eat. Now she is mostly a predator, hunting animals.” \r
\r
The story finishes with noses nuzzling and a family goodbye. Autumn has arrived and the year’s cycle is complete, with offspring now grown enough to seek their own territories: “Vixen watches them go, red coats ablaze, their white-tipped tails floating like banners.” An extensive afterword offers more facts about red foxes, including this canine’s particularly unique similarities to felines. Altogether, this is a wonderful natural science resource as well as an excellent model of the narrative non-fiction genre.""" ;
    ns2:title "Secret Life of the Red Fox" ;
