    ns2:reviewBody "This wordless picture book explores the boundaries of imagination in a story about the courage required to make new friends. A little girl hears children chatting in a treehouse just outside her new home, but she’s too shy to join them. Idly, she picks at the wallpaper and, when a bird flies out, she peels the paper back to discover she can enter an alternate world. Among the flock of birds and outsized plants, a three-eyed, sharp-fanged spiky yellow monster is after her—or so she thinks. She tries to escape, deking in and out of the wallpaper landscapes, until the monster gives up, and sits down, in tears. Realizing that the monster just wanted to be friends, the girl finds the courage to greet it (and the fear it symbolizes), and together they eat ice cream, blow dandelions clocks, and play among clouds and rainbows. When her stomach grumbles, the girl heads back to the real world for a snack, and then can’t get back into the wallpaper world. But her experience with the friendly monster has emboldened her to approach the kids in the treehouse. The collage illustrations evoke multiple imaginative and psychological layers: the imagined universe suggested by images, our natural timidity at approaching strangers, and the way creative play can establish emotional and behavioural patterns for the real world. The cut paper shapes and myriad contrasting textures are an apt metaphor for the complex task of unpacking how it feels to be the new kid, and how brave it is to go toward the unknown. The wallpaper world is colourful and friendly, with the shapes acting as portals into seemingly infinite settings—a tropical forest, a frog-filled pond, an expanse of bubbles filled with sheep. Even the monster from which the protagonist flees is ostensibly harmless and ultimately approachable. The illustrations are broken up into graphic-novel–like frames, which pace the narrative and create a familiar structure." ;
