    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Peachtree Publishing Company"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book about a young boy’s early interactions with bees through his extended family addresses themes of patience, communication and attention. Henry and his aunt Lilla live in the country, where they tend a vegetable garden, keep chickens and have beehives. Aunt Lilla explains the basics of beekeeping—“A bee won’t sting you unless you get in the way of what she’s doing,” she explains to her nephew, pointing out that almost all the bees are “sister bees,” and telling him about their “talking dance.” Henry has an acute sense of fairness, and his natural curiosity draws him to the bees, humming and dancing as if he were one of the insects. When the bees seem ready to swarm, Aunt Lilla sets up another hive nearby and Henry draws the bees over. The text is lengthy but fairly straightforward, and the dialogue, especially Aunt Lilla’s dialect (“We got to do all we can to keep ‘em here”) defines a sense of place and class. \r
The watercolour and ink two-page colour spreads provide an artful, peaceful representation of life in the country—Henry and his aunt looking after the bees, Henry gathering an armful of eggs in the henhouse, Aunt Lilla hoeing in the garden. Frequent inset details, such as the queen on a honeycomb with workers hovering around, show close-ups of Henry and Lilla’s discussions about bees. The boy’s attention and his almost philosophical demeanour are captured through his expressive face and body language. Illustrations of the beekeeping equipment are accurate and beautiful, and the setting as a whole seems bucolic and paradisial.""" ;
