    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A tremendous variety of self-expression is gathered in this compelling anthology that focuses on the Valentine’s Day school shooting in Parkland, FLA, 2018—created by students and staff who were there: “I sit in my room, with my best friend,moments after escaping the end.We watch the news flash by . . . we listen to names. Rumors float byOf those who left us, I want to cry . . . The sounds ensue. A dreadful song.I do not believe in heaven. But I hopeI am wrong.”\r
Personal essays, poems, artwork and candid photos create a vivid, visual mosaic throughout this fairly lengthy book—a skillful reflection of the whirl of impression and emotion experienced on that terrible day and beyond. Scanned handwritten pages contribute an added sense of immediacy to the writings. One photo shows a scene of a protest crowd, where a girl holds up a beautifully rendered painting of a teen, hands raised, wearing a t-shirt that reads “DON’T SHOOT,” as lettering above and below urges: “Protect Kids Not Guns.”\r
Throughout the book, fear and sadness are tempered by empowerment, activism and healing in poems such as “puppy therapy: misty” and a speech brought before congress, “Nothing Bad Ever Happens in Parkland.” Back material offers hotlines, websites and books that can help with grief, anxiety, depression or PTSD.""" ;
