ns2:Book4eb9e8e7-d2b4-46e5-955c-f541c9e839ae a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Amanda Li" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54929" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Andrews McMeel Publishing"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The true adventures of children and young adults offer inspiring models for achievement in sport, science, music, invention, policy-making, survival and human rights. Vibrant illustrated spreads depict key moments in the lives of the people featured. Colourful design grids provide appealing backdrops for each story’s sidebars, which offer related information, such as identifying the instruments in an orchestra, tips for fending off a crocodile attack, details about ‘outswimming” an avalanche, tricks to learning public speaking, how to write jokes, and much more. \r
Skill, intelligence, bravery and determination: this inspiring book of true adventures offers 29 biographical profiles of children and young adults around the world, who met enormous challenges to achieve their dreams.\r
“The blue sea sparkled in the Greek sunshine.” Narrative language distills key moments for each profile: “Boyan felt himself getting angry. Why were people dumping so much plastic in the oceans? What would happen to all the sea creatures if this continued?” “How-to” sidebars (“The Plastic Problem” and “You Can Help”) direct the focus back onto readers, with related information (“Every year about eight million tons of plastic enters our oceans”) for action and involvement: “If you see plastic on the beach, pick it up and throw it in the trash.” \r
Along with well-known activists such as Greta Thunberg and Malala Yousafzai, readers will meet youth such as blind teenager Louis Braille, inventor of an alphabet; golfer Pratima Sherpa, born and raised in a Nepalese golf-course shed; William Kamkwamba, who brought wind-power to his starving village. Eye-popping tales of survival include Juliane Koepke’s solo trek through the Peruvian rainforest (“She understood that finding water was vital”) and Yeonmi Park’s escape from North Korea: “There were armed guards along the river and they were ready to shoot anyone who tried to cross it.” \r
The fully illustrated spreads are rich with colour—in scenes, spot images and sidebar backgrounds. Chess player Phiona Mutesi’s segment shows her as an illiterate child, bright-eyed over a game of chess; a checkerboard backdrop recedes behind her. The subsequent spread shows her wreathed in medals, carrying a trophy (“At 11 years old, Phiona won the Ugandan Women’s Junior Championship”). The sidebars depict chess pieces against background shades of pink and turquoise. Captions describe their respective moves and offer advice to “Perfect Your Skills.” \r
We may not all find ourselves repelling a shark, spying on a wartime enemy, battling depression with a career in stand-up comedy, or taking a solo journey around the world in a sailboat. But the collective message of this uplifting book is clear: we can all be heroes in one way or another. We can all strive—and we can all choose to inspire.""" ;
