    ns2:publisher ns2:Owlkids ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This contemporary fable begins with a few scraps of paper flying artfully across blank pages. “Where did they come from?” asks the text. “Whose are they?” Many animals claim responsibility in the creation of these scraps. The theme will be familiar to beginner readers: “They’re mine!” says the chicken. “No, They’re mine!” argues the fish. The bird, the snail and others also believe they have claims—each having been engaged in some activity with the papers.\r
Masterful, graphic illustrations feature the scraps in various configurations that actually form the contentious animals. Young children may insist on finding each scrap in its new role, picture after picture. It’s a brilliant manoeuvre that underlines the story’s message of collective contribution and ownership. It is the wind that finally brings this larger perspective, as the scraps topple and turn: “I’ll blow and blow as hard as I can . . . And with one last gust, I’ll blow them over to you.” Readers are thus invited: “They’re yours now too. What will you do?” This also offers an opportunity for the creation of new works, using similar shapes, among young students of art and geometry.""" ;
