    ns2:datePublished "2009"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Little_Brown ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Nubs, so named for his cropped ears, is the leader of a pack of wild dogs. He has never had a home to speak of, and struggles to survive in the harsh Iraqi desert. \r
Everything changes when Major Brian Dennis, a US Marine, meets the Iraqi dog of war and offers him meals, care and attention, and a warm place to sleep. There is only one problem: pets are not permitted in the Marines. \r
This does not stop Nubs from embarking on a 70-mile trek across the frozen desert to be reunited with Dennis after he is relocated. When events threaten to separate them again, Dennis sends a request home for money to help him fly Nubs back to the US, where they eventually become inseparable. \r
The story is made compelling by Dennis’ heartfelt first-person account, including vivid details of the dog’s emotional states: “Starving and exhausted from his ordeal, Nubs wolfed down pancakes, eggs and sausages...”; “He made dog-angels, rolling over and over in the freshly fallen snow.” \r
A visually rich combination of photographs, maps and Dennis’ emails home fuel this poignant narrative about the sheer power of friendship.""" ;
