ns2:Book5c53f2b4-3cee-4911-97d0-9172466721d9 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jonathan Litton" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54383" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Tiger Tales"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This intriguing book about Earth appeals to a scientific desire for facts and a poetic need for wonder: “Our planet is insignificant in the vastness of space, but hugely significant for the plants and animals that call it home. It’s a middle-aged space rock, about halfway through its natural life, containing multiple layers of intrigue….” \r
Four sections, “Physical Earth,” “Life on Earth,” “Earth Regions,” “Human Planet,” cover a range of topics both general: “The Tree of Life,” “Animal Habitats,” and specific: “Super Survivalists,” such as bacteria and cockroaches, and “Unsung Earthlings,” such as bees and fungi. \r
Artful colour illustrations with hand-drawn effects depict panoramic vistas, full of detail and captions. In the spread “How the Earth was Formed,” atmospheric scratch-art creates lively whorls around a crayon-yellow sun. At the top of the spread “How the WEATHER WORKS,” splotchy snow mountains and pencil crayon precipitation begin “The Water Cycle,” while a cutaway section at the bottom of the page illustrates concepts such as infiltration, groundwater, and leaf transpiration. \r
Of particular interest are the unique perspectives conveyed by lyrical language. The “Welcome” preface describes Earth as “an ever-changing environment filled with fleeting beauty—99 percent of species that have ever existed are now extinct for one reason or another.” A summary on the planet’s formation reads, “So there you have it: Earth is made from ancient stardust, as are all Earthlings.” Altogether, this attractive book offers a cohesive and interconnected approach to examining our planet and our place within its sphere.""" ;
