ns2:Book5cb6be56-e21e-45de-b5b5-3c53ee211a6b a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Elly MacKay" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56439" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Perseus Books – Running Press Kids"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This wordless picture book frames the familiar story of The Nutcracker within another story about a young girl’s discovery of the classic holiday ballet. A mother goes out one night, leaving her grumpy daughter in her grandmother’s care. It’s raining and windy out, but Gran braves the weather to bring the girl to the theatre. The framing plot of the girl shifts between her fascination with the ballet unfolding and her annoyance at a boy sitting nearby, who pesters her incessantly. The ballet is shown through key recognizable scenes like the little sheep and Mother Ginger, and the girl is increasingly smitten, finally communicating her delight to her seatmate. When the curtain drops, they say goodbye happily, and the girl dances home with her grandmother through the falling snow. The emphasis on structure through multiple plotlines and the emotional reactions and evolution of the characters create a layered response that is both relatable for readers and makes for its own theatre. \r
The papercraft illustrations combine ink and watercolour to create a sense of depth and decoupage. The human figures are set apart from the more ephemeral backgrounds; this lends a sense of theatricality to the story itself, which is achieved through divisions in the framing of the story into acts. A sense of the surreal in the blurred features and peaked bodies of the dancers sets the ballet world apart from the girl’s, as does the use of colour: while the story taking place on stage is depicted in bright colours, the girl’s life is mostly tinted in greys, pale blues, and sepia tones. Some of the illustrations are full-page, while others are broken up into rectangular or inset panels, often in moments at which the audience reacts to particular scenes (such as the battle between the rat king and the nutcracker prince).""" ;
    ns2:title "Waltz of the Snowflakes" ;
