    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This informative and fascinating book looks at the ways in which forensic science is used to solve current and historical mysteries. The book presents seven unsolved cases from history, beginning with a mass grave site found in ancient Mayan ruins and ending with Marie Antoinette’s son, who supposedly died in prison at age 10.\r
The text is informative, at times humorous, and is broken into subsections that present the plot, suspects, clues, methods of analysis and final verdict. Chapters also include a narrative that serves to recreate the incident: “Tut stood up slowly, putting all his weight on his walking stick. The throbbing in his feet was getting worse.” Using photographs, diagrams and images from scans, the methodology of each investigation is explained. In King Tut’s case, since DNA can become contaminated over thousands of years, “one way of extracting ‘clean’ DNA is to thoroughly clean one of the mummy’s teeth, then drill to the inner pulp and extract the DNA there.” This is how they discovered that Tut’s parents were brother and sister and that he almost certainly was not murdered but died of malaria.\r
In addition to investigating historical mysteries, the text explains how the various technologies are used in contemporary crime scenes: “A CT scan can trace the path of the bullet, show how the brain was damaged, where bleeding occurred and more.” An accompanying photo shows King Tut’s CT head scan. This riveting blend of storytelling, history and modern forensic techniques is both educational and entertaining.""" ;
