    ns2:datePublished "2006"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """D.J. arrived at his new school a month ago and is not feeling very welcome. A boy named Vince likes to pick on him with taunting remarks, always claiming that he is “just kidding.” D.J. can’t just laugh it away: “Back at my old school, my friends would joke around with me, but they never made me feel like I was a joke.” His supportive family and teachers help him come up with a strategy to deflect the bullying.\r
Part of a series on building character and preventing bullying, the focus here is when ‘kidding around’ has an edge. Through rich text, written from D.J.’s point of view, we gain insight into his world and feelings. His dad advises: “You may never know why kids like Vince are mean to you. But I do think it has more to do with what’s going on with him than with you.”\r
Realistic painted illustrations often fill double page spreads. Clever layouts include the bus driver scowling in the rear view mirror or D.J. running alone surrounded by white space. The children’s facial expressions and body language add to the humanity of the storytelling.\r
Useful resources on the nuances of bullying, discussion questions, do’s and don’ts and a reading list are also provided.""" ;
