ns2:Book66b58e3b-4b2b-4b83-b109-69be75108b85 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jonathan London" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52132" ;
    ns2:datePublished "1998"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Fitzhenry___Whiteside ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this story about empathy and discovering a fresh point of view, readers are offered a close-up encounter with a tiny yellow spider in her forest habitat. \r
\r
Expressive language is imbued with a sense of immediacy through the uncommon device of putting the story in second person singular: “. . . Yellow Spider’s web shimmers, like a wind across a pond. But she hangs on and you stay with her.”\r
Illustrations with an oil pastel effect are soft-edged and saturated with colour, seeming to emit their own light. Most pictures fill the space in a full-page bleed; the few spot illustrations shine like little jewels. One image shows a big-eyed child looming over the bright spider and her glistening web. Then the focus closes in: “Yellow Spider’s world is yours . . . .”\r
When a hiker stomps unheedingly through the web, young readers will relate to the sense of crisis—and relief—when the spider is found again and put back on her ravaged web. From tiny creatures to people to the stars, we are all part of a complex web. \r
\r
Back material offers fascinating spider facts for budding scientists.""" ;
