    ns2:datePublished "2005"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """On a flight from Vancouver to Toronto, horse-crazy Samantha and bookish Alexis listen enviously to the other’s vacation plans. Since their hosts have never met them, and their parents are far away, it makes perfect sense to trade places. By chance, the homes are close to each other, making it easy to strengthen their secret alliance. \r
Both humour and tension are present when the girls enter their hosts’ homes. “For a split second, Alex longed to run after one of the women and confess. The thought of keeping up such a complicated deception scared her.”\r
Presented in the third person, the author balances both girls’ points of view. Human relationships with horses and dogs abound, complemented by an overly talkative parrot who adds delightful craziness to the plot twists. \r
Family relationships, with their rivalry and loyalty are expertly explored, as well as a child’s yearning to be valued and accepted. In a non-judgmental tone, the story concludes with a family crisis and a touching and gratifying resolution, where truth wins out. The characters settle gratefully into who they really are.""" ;
