    ns2:datePublished "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Minedition ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Then the huge black cloud came.” Told from the perspective of Sadako’s pet cat, brief language describes an idyllic morning in the park (“We ate rice balls and lay in the grass”) before a dropped atom bomb lays all to waste. \r
The bulk of the tale, based on a true story, focuses on Sadako’s subsequent battle with leukemia—the result of her exposure to radiation. Delicate, stylized compositions in coloured pencil effects use subtle texture and intricate patterns—reminiscent of Japanese origami papers—to create scenes of the sick girl and her feline friend. In one image, origami cranes seem to float above her hospital bed. Another incorporates the step-by-step process of folding a paper crane. \r
Sadako’s commitment to folding 1,000 cranes symbolizes the two friends’ hopes and dreams of her recovery: “Then we will come home on the back of a giant dragon.” In the end, a series of spot illustrations revisits those unfulfilled dreams, now marked with inky paw-prints of the cat: “Now I carry Sadako’s story out into the world.” \r
An endnote discusses the real Sadako, the Children’s Peace Monument in Hiroshima and the continuing tradition of making paper cranes for peace.""" ;
    ns2:title "Sadako's Cranes" ;
