    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Caroline usually wakes up happy and singing in the morning, but not today: “Today Caroline lay still in her bed with her eyes closed, imagining the day before her. Today would be unusual.” A book on her bedroom floor reads: “Your New Adopted Sibling.” \r
\r
Caroline struggles all day. She forgets her lunch, accidently knocks out a classmate’s loose tooth, and makes a mess at the art centre. The text is creative and at times poetic: “Caroline smiled, but she felt slightly strange, like the space where Wendy’s tooth once was.” \r
\r
The detailed, inviting illustrations are a mix of ink, watercolour and collage featuring a pastel palette. One page shows Caroline’s teacher reading to the class. Her classmates are rendered in faded greys, while Caroline and her teacher are in full colour. Caroline is shown tilting back in her chair and nervously chewing her thumbnail: “She kept thinking about what would happen. Soon.” \r
When the bell rings and Caroline goes outside, her parents are waiting for her. They are dishevelled but wearing giant grins and carrying: “a bundle from far, far away.” \r
\r
Even though Caroline is nervous about today: “This baby made everything, every usual thing, unusually new and perfectly right.” The final scene shows Caroline beaming at her new sister, surrounded by her parents and grandmother on the front steps.""" ;
