    ns2:publisher ns2:Roaring_Brook_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody "Earth is our “Goldilocks planet” because it “has everything ‘just right’ for us.” The text opens by explaining the elements that make our planet habitable, including temperature, liquid water and its molten core, which is “swirling with so much iron that it creates a magnetic field strong enough to protect our atmosphere from the solar wind.” The watercolour illustrations are full of bright colours and feature a wide-eyed young girl and her family at a “Searching for Exoplanets” exhibition. While her parents examine the molten core diagram, she perceives the floor becoming an open pit of glowing hot magma and steam. As her family enters the planetarium, the girl turns back to examine the winking, wobbling, colourful stars, all indicators of planets. The text manages to explain complex concepts in a way that is concrete and easy to grasp: “A wink tells us that an orbiting planet blocks some of the star’s light each time it passes between the stars and us.” The girl also lingers on a rendition of one of the rocky planets of TRAPPIST-1 featuring a red landscape with several nearby planets. The book asks readers what we could do if we found evidence of beings like ourselves and offers suggestions such as sending “solutions to useful math problems” or “art and poetry and music.” The text implies the likelihood of life elsewhere and offers some visual possibilities while acknowledging that these planets and their inhabitants could also be “nothing like we can even imagine.”" ;
