    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Sterling Children’s Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture-book biography of American feminist Gloria Steinem introduces young readers to her work and to some of the basic tenets of feminism. Steinem is presented first as a child, dreaming of fame and of helping people. Seeing her mother’s own professional ambitions trumped by the social expectations and impositions on women struck Steinem as “very unfair,” even at an early age, and her mother’s mental illness and their financial struggles after the divorce made an impression on her. The book explores Steinem’s work as a journalist, and her cross-country activism with Dorothy Pitman Hughes—an attempt to make their voices heard that leads to the founding of Ms. magazine. Written in clear, short sentences, the story creates a clear causal link between women being relegated to frivolous and household matters, and the foundational and ever-relevant principles of second-wave feminism. The book concludes with a more factual one-page biography of Steinem, a list of suggestions for further reading, and notes about major moments and figures mentioned in the story. \r
\r
The watercolour, gouache, pencil and digital illustrations are both representative and figurative interpretations of several important moments and symbols in Steinem’s life—she is shown at her typewriter before a window through which we see the New York City skyline, for instance, while the next page focuses on her hands typing as pages blow away over a tiny cowering figure of Steinem. A few pages later, she is standing proudly on the keys, hands on her hips, red hair blowing in the wind. The flowery details, with pastel pink tones are suggestive of the gender tropes and stereotypes reclaimed by feminists. Other figures depict the diversity of who is and can be a feminist—the lineup of people waiting to get a copy of Ms., for example, and an image showing rows of portraits of different women, which is at the heart of the book and reprised in the front and endpapers.""" ;
    ns2:title "Gloria’s Voice: The Story of Gloria Steinem—Feminist, Activist, Leader" ;
