ns2:Book69a9ad79-a388-4dee-a493-1bb6f32b5a02 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Maria Gianferrari" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56784" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Brown_Books_for_Young_Readers ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Tree communicate, help and heal one another through support networks, “a wood wide web of information,” and we can do the same. \r
\r
This convincing analogy between trees and humans teaches fascinating facts about trees (“We purify the air. We anchor the soil, preventing erosion”), while offering a role model for human community too: “Our bodies and branches and roots are homes to birds and mammals and insects. We sustain ecosystems.” \r
\r
Poetic language helps students understand botany by relating it to our own anatomies: “Beneath your bark are layers, such as sapwood, carrying nutrients to help you grow bigger and taller; and heartwood, strong as bone, to support you”. This ingenious approach also encourages interest, empathy and a sense of responsibility: “Wave your leaves in the wind, breathe in the air, drink in sun, let them fuel you and the world.” \r
\r
Detailed, hand-rendered illustrations in paint and colour-pencil effects combine science and symbol in colourful and surreal compositions. One beautiful spread relates the cross-section of a tree trunk to our own circulatory system. On the far right, the white shadow of a human figure pops against the dark background, with red and blue pathways coursing the torso and limbs. On the far left the cross-section of a tree trunk radiates. The colourful centre, rich with abstracted forms, recalls a cell-nucleus—or maybe a pretty garden, viewed from high above. Thick, swirling trails emerge, carrying particles across the tree rings, the page gutter and toward the human figure, recalling the flow of blood cells. (“In your hearts’ center is your pith, keeper of nutrients when you were a sapling.”) Another spread shows a cutaway scene of thick, coiling trees and their root-systems underground. White lines with dots of blue, white and red suggest neural pathways, or an electronic circuit board. (“Our roots twine with fungi, joining all trees in the forest together.”) Above ground, an abundance of child-characters play among the intertwined branches. (“We talk, share food, store water, divide resources, alert each other to danger.”) \r
\r
The book’s call for a more tree-like attitude among people is made explicit in a double-page foldout spread, showing a bearded man in a cap, huddling alone with his bag on a park bench. (“Immigrant trees, away from their native habitats, are vulnerable.”) The spread opens to reveal the same scene, now filled with people, running, playing, picnicking—and the same man on the bench, now sitting with his family. (“Mother trees nurse young trees. Old trees shade new trees. Strong trees shelter weak trees. Healthy trees help sick trees.”) Two final images complete the analogy: the first is an artful composition of a forest – home for a tremendous variety of tree-shapes and sizes; the second shows a gathering of the people  who are characters that appear the book: “So, be a tree. for together, we are a forest.” \r
\r
Green-hued end papers depict (with captions) leaves, seeds and fruits of nearly two dozen tree species. Back material further addresses the book’s dual theme, discussing ways readers can save trees, and foster a better community for our human ‘forest’.""" ;
