    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Fire-Mouth has the kingdom of Mirador terrified. The beast is as horrible as it is mysterious. Few have ever seen it, but it is known to be as monstrous as a wolf, to be bigger and stronger than a bull and to devour children. When three saltimbancos and their circus dog, Cocoa-pod, come to town, they find a populace petrified—in Mirador, no one has danced or sung since the beast arrived. Instead of hunting, facing or fearing Fire-Mouth, however, the musicians suggest taming it with music. The beast is nowhere to be seen, but the townsfolk are transformed. The music inspires them to rediscover singing, dancing, gardening and even love! But King Minus prefers to govern by fear and he hatches a ploy to frame Cocoa-pod.\r
The performers use musical terms and forms—seguidilla, flamenco, fandango, passacaglia and others are mentioned in passing—as are arpeggio, tremolo and trill. The rich vocabulary is evocative, while dialogue gives voice to the three performers, the king and the townspeople.\r
The story is illustrated with oil paintings made to look like collage (bits of paper glued together). The stylized naïve, bright colours and colonial architecture evoke Picasso’s native Spain. The book reproduces the Picasso painting from which the story is spun, as well as simply outlined biographical and background facts about Picasso, his work and techniques, and the story’s three harlequins.""" ;
