ns2:Book6c045ca8-17e4-4b73-99c8-9331a0266701 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jill MacLean" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52858" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Pajama_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Do we all have hidden lives?” asks 15-year-old Nix. The pain of being trapped behind walls of unexpressed emotion, unspoken truths and lies figures prominently in this first-person narrative about the yearning for freedom and self-expression.\r
A tightly crafted plot guides the reader through experiences that shatter Nix’s isolation and sense of security. Bullied at school, he has difficulties with self-expression and is plunged into a “head-on-collision” relationship with his rebellious sister Roxy.\r
On top of it all, he has overprotective parents who burden him with an unachievable sense of sibling responsibility, causing a rift between Nix and his sister. Nix does have moments of peace, particularly in his love for a neglected neighbourhood dog named Twig, in whose eyes he “never saw such sadness, such hopelessness.” Stark, descriptive imagery of rural Newfoundland graces the book with a welcome sense of openness to balance characters’ closed interior landscapes.\r
Sharp, spare wording provides immediacy and depth to characters’ emotions as they grapple with tragedy and grief, “so heavy on my chest I can’t breathe,” and guilt at the failure to protect those they love. The author depicts grief as a process that ultimately leads to acceptance, a deeper connection to others, emotional courage and hope.""" ;
