    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """William Carlos Williams’ famous poem “This is Just to Say” is the inspiration for this humorous anthology of 46 tongue-in-cheek apologies featuring familiar fairy tale characters such as Sleeping Beauty and Little Red Riding Hood. In one, Rapunzel admits she lopped off her braid because the man climbing it is “not worth the pain in my scalp.” In another, after chewing the stem off Jack’s beanstalk, the cow huffily explains, “I think I’m worth more than five magic beans.”\r
Playfully subverting the conventions of a book, the author’s introduction also comes in the form of an insincere apology for its unusual placement (not at the beginning), and also coaxes readers to pen a poem of their own, following these simple rules: “The first stanza states the horrible offense. The second stanza describes the effect of the offense. The last stanza begins with ‘Forgive me’ and continues with the false apology, because the writer is not sorry at all.” \r
A funky table of contents, alternating page orientation and black and white line drawings reminiscent of Shel Silverstein round out this entertaining read-aloud.""" ;
