    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Fans of skateboards and woodworking, and aspiring artists of all stripes, will appreciate this profile of a skateboard-maker that includes biographical details, Jake Eschelman’s work process and a timeline of skateboarding history: “1976-1978—The California drought leaves swimming pools empty. The Zephyrs use these empty pools and create a new skating move known as Vert, for vertical skating.”\r
The dynamic design incorporates a drafting-grid background, pencil markings and tools of the trade to support an abundance of photography that includes old family photos, step-by-step shots of skateboard construction and images of skateboarding fun. One spread shows a beat-up, black-and-white snapshot of a boy captured mid-leap, high in the air above his board: “Jake’s father-in-law in the 1960s.” The photo for “Step 9” shows Jake at work, Ipod peeking from his back pocket—with which, readers have been informed, “he turns on the heavy metal music that he loves.”\r
The spread “Now It’s Your Turn” encourages readers to consider hand-crafting their own objects (“how can you turn a bottle cap or a paper plate or an empty spool of thread into something brand-new?”), driving home the book’s key message about the pleasure of hand-working materials, developing skills and enjoying a sense of accomplishment. As Jake himself counsels: “Be honest with yourself about what fires your passion. Above all, feel comfortable and unafraid to take chances.”""" ;
