ns2:Book78ad9488-4bcb-4e87-9ee2-09fde8d65368 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Robert Macfarlane" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54470" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Language and art are skillfully intertwined in this large illustrated volume of acrostic poetry. The collection examines uncommon words of the natural world (words that have been “lost” according to the introduction) using rich vocabulary and clever imagery.\r
Each poem is a unique feat of thought and structure, even within the imposed acrostic structure that uses the letters in a word to inspire the start of each line in the poem. “Fern’s first form is furled,” explains the first line of “Fern”: “Each frond fast as a fiddle-head.” The H in “heron” proclaims, “Here hunts heron. Here haunts heron. Huge-hinged heron. Grey-winged weapon.”\r
An abundance of deft watercolour illustrations surround each poem. First, an artful spread combines abstracted natural forms with letter-jumbles, in which readers may hunt out the featured word. Next, the word and its poem are featured in a spread that includes a meticulous portrait of each subject, in the manner of illustrated natural science dictionaries. A final double-page illustration portrays each specimen in its natural habitat. For example, in the illustration accompanying “starling,” the bird’s subtle colouring is shown through a still pose. The subsequent spread bursts with flight, as flocks speed across the foreground and undulate en masse in the far distance. From “adder,” “bramble” and “conker,” through “ivy,” “otter” and so much more, the language and images of this inventive book brings its lost world to life.""" ;
    ns2:title "Lost Words: A Spell Book" ;
    ns1:isCoupDeCoeur false ;
