    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Lerner"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Conversational language and flamboyant watercolour images combine to create this natural science picture book about the role flowers’ colours play in the process of pollination, as explained by a feisty cactus: “We sit here growing, minding our own business while you guys go on about how red roses stand for love… What a load of fertilizer!” \r
Expressive and gorgeous watercolour illustrations depict a profusion of blossoms, while interpreting seed life cycles, wafts of ‘flower-speak’ (“come on over. We have a special treat for you”) and whimsical images of the cactus-narrator (“What would you do if your legs were stuck in the ground for your entire life?”), as it eyes a slice of pizza (“How would you eat?’), gets tangled with a tea-bag (“How would you drink?”) and more (“How would you get your pajamas on?”). One picture shows a fuzzy, pollen-drenched bee. Its bulbous eyes reflect the blue blossom from which it drinks: “They have special pockets on their legs to carry pollen home to their young.” Another shows a gathering of moths and bats over a field of white flowers: “And when it’s dark outside. What color shows up best?” \r
Colours red, yellow, purple, brown and green—and even blossom structure—all have their meanings and messages in this imaginative and informative book. Illustrated back material includes descriptions of flower anatomy, pollination and pollinator conservation.""" ;
