    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """When the government drafts an aging man into the army, his young daughter, proficient in horsemanship, archery and martial arts, decides to disguise herself as a man and go to war . . . to fulfill her father’s duty to protect the country. In the dozen years Mulan serves on the front lines, earning the respect of her comrades, her gender and identity are never discovered. That is, not until she returns home and publicly reveals who she really is. \r
With just a few sentences per page, written in both English and simplified Chinese characters, this engaging read-aloud privileges themes of family honour and duty over those of war and violence, making this retelling of an old folktale suitable for younger audiences.\r
Spreads of gentle ink paintings draw readers in and dramatize the action in each scene: family life in a traditional Chinese home, adventures in the battlefield, a ceremonial welcome at the Emperor’s palace. \r
A brief bilingual note at the end locates the story’s origins in a 1500-year-old narrative poem that has been passed down from generation to generation.""" ;
