    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Boxer Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This book provides a brief look at a well-known dinosaur, the T. Rex, using real objects to show the scale of these beasts. “Its eyes were as big as baseballs,” reads the text while the illustration, done in linocuts and collograph with digital colour, shows the T. Rex’s head on one page while on the opposite page its skull appears with a baseball in the eye socket. The illustrations contain a great deal of texture, but the details are cartoonish and the palette mostly limited to browns and yellows. One page shows a T. Rex footprint surrounded by brown, cracked earth. Inside are tiny human footprints in various colours: “37 children’s footprints could fit inside one T. Rex footprint!” \r
\r
Each page features a new, simple, relatable fact. It’s not until the end that the book reveals the answer to the question: “But how tall was a T. Rex?” The illustration shows an angry-looking T. Rex with a measuring tape around its tail. On the next page there is a T. Rex beside 10 velociraptors, stacked one on top of the other. The following page has the T. Rex dwarfed by a massive brachiosaurus. Finally, the T. Rex faces a giraffe sticking out its tongue. They are the same height. A brief afterword lists various measurements for the T. Rex in feet and inches, and explains that “Scientists can tell a lot about dinosaurs by looking at bones and fossils.”""" ;
