    ns2:publisher ns2:Bloomsbury ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Livi is a little girl with a big imagination. Reluctant to get out of bed and ready for school, she turns this transition time into a great adventure: as a snail, going “sooooooooo . . . slooooooowwwwwwww . . . across the floor” and as a pirate, digging through her drawers for underwear. She is a Sherpa, lifting her heavy backpack; a kangaroo, hopping to the school bus; an “Ol’ Wild West woman,” getting into a covered wagon (the bus). She sashays to class, waving to the paparazzi, and enjoys the day.\r
Digital illustrations are exuberant, boldly depicting Livi’s wild imagination in a playful cartoon style. Mainly dwelling in the world of make-believe, they occasionally snap back to the real bus, the real Livi and her real mom, allowing for some pretty spectacular contrasts. Images are action-packed, full of adventures and exotic settings – from the red carpet to Mount Everest.\r
Language is rich with Livi’s voice recounting her every move: “I am a Sherpa, and I will lead a group of fearless explorers . . . We’ll be gone for weeks and will have to live on potato chips and old turkey sandwiches.” The adult voices of reason interject in speech bubbles throughout: “Do you have everything?” “Good morning, class! Let’s begin!”\r
This dynamic read-aloud encourages creating fun from even the most mundane things in life.""" ;
