ns2:Book7dcb82f6-703e-463f-b876-7c007c90395e a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Matt de la Peña" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56788" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "G.P. Putnam’s Sons"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Milo goes on a long subway ride with his big sister. Along the way, he watches the other passengers and imagines their lives. He draws his daydreams in his sketchbook and shows them to his sister, but she’s not really paying attention. They both have their minds on something else. A new passenger boards: a boy with perfect hair and new shoes. Milo imagines he will disembark into his coach and be driven by horses to his castle. He imagines the woman in the wedding dress will fly away in a hot-air balloon with her groom, and more. When their stop finally arrives, the boy is surprised to see the little prince ahead of him: they are both visiting the same building. They both go through the metal detector. Milo’s sister apologizes for being short with him earlier. When they finally arrive, Milo spots his mom in the crowd of other prisoners, receiving visitors. The three of them hug and finally everything feels right. Milo shows his mom the picture he drew for her: Himself, his mom and his sister on their front stoop, eating ice cream together. \r
\r
Evocative and complex vocabulary brings to life this engaging and mysterious tale about the power of imagination: “What begins as a slow, distant glow grows and grows into a tired train that clatters down the tracks. A cool rush of wind quiets into a screech of steel, and when the doors slide open, Milo slips aboard.” \r
As the language describes Milo’s fellow passengers (“The wedding-dressed woman near the far door has a face made of light”), on his notepad, Milo draws his imaginings about their lives. This helps distract him from his own feelings: “Excitement stacked on top of worry on top of confusion on top of love.” Skillfully planted clues contribute interest and mystery to the plot: “These monthly Sunday subway rides are never ending, and as usual, Milo is a shook-up soda” “Milo tugs his sister’s sleeve and holds up his picture. But even when she turns to look, he can tell she doesn’t see. She’s a shook-up soda, too.” And “his mom’s soothing voice reading him a bedtime book over the phone…” \r
\r
Milo’s rich storylines touch on socio-economic differences (“the boy is met by a butler, two maids, and a gourmet chef offering crust-free sandwich squares”), stereotypes and profiling (“…faces still follow their every move. When they walk down the electronics aisle at the department store. When they cross into the fancy neighborhood”) and even his own biases: “Milo tries to reimagine all the pictures he made on the train. Maybe he could have done it like this instead. Or this. Or this.” \r
\r
Charming hand-painted illustrations combine a naive simplicity with a strong graphic awareness. Milo’s tiny face is almost buried under round spectacles and a massive woollen toque. His sister’s braids are pulled into a tight top-knot; she wears a bright pink coat. As Milo scribbles in his pad, she takes selfies and plays games on her phone. The landscape-format, double-page spreads create long subway car compositions, rich with individuated characters. Across one spread, a trio of break-dancers flip and turn in the foreground. Their bright, patterned outfits mingle and clash with the row of seated passengers behind. (“And now the girls are walking up walls, they’re whirling around poles….”) \r
\r
Milo’s own drawings alternate with the ‘real-life’ images, simple coloured pencil sketches in child-like line and scribbled-in fills. One spread shows his open notebook, with all the re-imagined drawings: the lonely whiskered man in the walk-up now eats dinner with his family. The bride is with another bride, under a bower of green leaves. And the break-dancers now troop into the fancy apartment building with a smiling doorman, whose speech bubble reads, “Welcome home!” \r
\r
In the end, this poignant book synthesizes all the contrasts that life—and the imagination—can offer, with its loving jailhouse reunion and Milo’s own picture of their family, together on the outside: “‘I made this for you,’ he says, holding it up. And he watches for the smile he hopes will spread across his mom’s face.”""" ;
    ns2:title "Milo Imagines the World" ;
