    ns2:publisher ns2:Houghton_Mifflin_Harcourt ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Jeremy Jacob is at the beach with his family when he spots a pirate ship approaching. While his parents are distracted, he accepts Captain Braid Beard’s invitation to join the crew, as long as he can be back in time for soccer practice the next day. He discovers he enjoys the life of a pirate, doing whatever he wants, eating what he likes and staying up late, until he realizes there are no bedtime stories or good-night kisses on board, and that he misses his family after all. \r
Told from the point of view of the boy, the story includes plenty of good pirate vocabulary to stir a reader’s imagination and encourage the class to join in during read-alouds: “Ahoy thar, matey,” “Shiver me timbers,” “Swab the deck,” “Batten down the hatches,” and more. \r
Acrylic paintings in realistic detail capture the characters’ expressive faces and the humour in the plot, and depict the pirates as a lively, happy-go-lucky bunch of men. The layout employs full-bleed single and double spreads and oversized font to capture the pirates’ grand exclamations.\r
Accompanying the protagonist on his swashbuckling adventure, readers will come to understand that freedom isn’t always as great as it seems.""" ;
