ns2:Book80ed75dd-1567-4fa3-9d8e-7c8c968e072a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andrew Larsen" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55456" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Owlkids ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A child wakes up in a bad mood. They don’t like anything about his day and they definitely don’t want to hear any stories about these things. Breakfast, school, lunch, the bus ride home—none of these things make good stories. Meanwhile, their cat enjoys a range of parallel adventures and mishaps while waiting for the child’s return. Once the pair are reunited, the child’s scowl turns to a smile, even as their objections continue to narrate the afternoon’s progress into evening. Finally, tucked in bed, they admit that a story about a cat might be good: “Do you know any stories about a cat?” Deadpan humour embellishes this appealing tale about a child having a bad day. Direct, minimal language artfully conveys the grumpy voice of a child who wakes up in a bad mood, and grudgingly endures each step of his daily routine: “I do not like stories about waking up in the morning.” \r
\r
Charming line drawings are filled with muted blue-grays and accents of orange and yellow. Their visual narratives skillfully expand on the language: as the child dresses, the cat plays with their space-themed mobile—knocking the child on the head. “I do not like stories about people in space… or fish in the sea.” (As the child feeds the goldfish in its bowl and the cat watches with intense interest.) “I do not like…” As the language plays variations on its refrain, images portray a dual storyline of the pair’s respective days. The child goes to school (“I do not like stories about boring old buildings”), sits in class (“I do not like stories about numbers or letters”). While in a parallel sequence, the cat sneaks out of the house and upsets a mail carrier with a bag full of mail. (Letters and numbers… again!) \r
\r
Readers may wish to identify all the parallels between the cat’s dramatic hijinks and the child’s daily routine. They may also wish to tell—or write—the cat’s wordless storyline. As the child listlessly pokes at their lunch (“I do not like stories about apples or pears or peaches or plums”), a comic-style sequence depicts the cat’s friendly approach to a fruit vendor, which ends in a tumbling cascade of her stock. During art time, the child’s tongue sticks out in effort, as they draws their cat (“I do not like stories about missing the one you love”) while the cat appears small and bereft in a series of busy cityscapes. Their eventual reunion sparks a subtle shift in the child’s mood, as the friends play together (“nothing to do”) and watch the night sky (“stars that come out at the end of the day”). The book’s unspoken message that stories create meaning from—and for—our lives is emphasized in final spreads that show the child tucked in bed with his cat… and a book: “Do you know any stories about cats?”""" ;
    ns2:title "I Do Not Like Stories" ;
    ns1:isCoupDeCoeur true ;
