ns2:Book8193458a-5d72-4448-9590-c6003cd2b546 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Martine Leavitt" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54011" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Tuk is a young bighorn sheep with a destiny to fulfill. He alone can lead the young ones in his diminishing herd to a new home where they will be safe from man’s encroachment and from predators taking advantage of their dwindling numbers. When Tuk and his companions set out for Blue Mountain, they bravely face threatening pumas, wolves, bears, wolverines and still more men.  \r
\r
The exciting plot includes the realities of birth, life and death in the wild. “Snow was falling fiercely ... and Tuk saw that Dos would not be able to stand up and paw away the snow to get his food. He would starve.” The text flows smoothly, grabbing readers’ attention with heightening tension as fearsome predators hunt and attack. With each situation, well-drawn characters grow to rely on, protect and value each other’s differences. “Tuk knew that Dall’s gentleness had always come out of strength. That was why they all loved her. That was why he loved her.” \r
\r
Clear text and vivid description create captivating images. “Tuk … held to the rocks beneath his feet as the puma ripped at his ear … He was a bighorn. He endured. Endured the cold and the storms of the high places … Endured the pain of puma ripping off his ear.”\r
\r
The conclusion will enhance readers’ appreciation for the wild and its creatures and deepen their understanding of the need to protect them.""" ;
