    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Beautiful, playful pen-and-ink drawings take readers on a tour of a country fair. Along the way they identify shapes. Each spread features one 2D shape, which is the only coloured element in the illustration. These include not only basic shapes like “square” and “triangle,” but also more obscure ones like “quatrefoil” and “trapezium.” \r
The tour of the fair is given by a little girl looking for her pet monster. From the start, readers are involved in the search and encouraged to examine the elements that make up a fair: “Has my monster been on this ride?” Onomatopoeic words describe the monster’s experience at the fair. “Maybe he – bump, bump, bump – came here,” says the girl at the bumper cars. Both images and words are used to describe the fair: “He loves music!” shows the monster leading a jaunty marching band. \r
A box in the top corner of the right-hand page tells readers which shape to look for. Sometimes the shape appears only once in the spread, sometimes many times. Each shape is a different vibrantly textured colour. \r
Never fear, in the end the monster is found and brought home under a crescent moon.""" ;
