    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Harper Teen"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The language comes out swinging in this rags-to-riches-to-rags story. Written in a free verse style that recalls a hip-hop beat, the narration is cool, sharp and very compelling. “Sara Bryant breezes into physics class, my friend. Like she’s better than you. Because she is.” Word lists paint vivid pictures among the prose, whether describing the student body (“Skaters. B-Girls. Baseheads …”), the mall (“Club Monaco. Gap. Gucci…”) or emotions: \r
Adam ducks back, suddenly aware of: \r
-His ten-dollar Walmart haircut. \r
-The pimple on his cheek.\r
-His crappy Payless shoes. \r
-His absolute loner status.\r
\r
Short lines build brief chapters that manage to convey volumes about characters and back story, while moving action forward at a clipping pace. \r
\r
Underdog Adam’s appetite and swagger are all part of the fun, until status and wealth cost him love, friendship and his own values: “—there’s no rationalizing what he did to Ryan Grant. Adam can’t explain Ryan Grant to Victoria. Or himself.” By the end, a humbler and wiser Adam begins to rebuild, on stronger foundations.""" ;
