    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The first page features a small half-drawn face and the words, “It started . . .” The next page reads, “with one mistake,” and shows the same face but with one too-big eye. The following pages follow the artist as she makes more mistakes and finds creative solutions for each one. She adds glasses to the too-big eyes and a ruffled collar with patterns of lace and stripes to the too-long neck. Each page builds in complexity with more mistakes and creative solutions.\r
The text is simple, playful and humorous: “The bush was another good idea, dark and leafy so that you couldn’t see through it . . . to the frog-cat-cow thing.” The illustration shows an ambiguous drawing of a cat with a frog leg and cow spots.\r
The many mistakes lead to the girl wearing pink roller blades with a black cap and trailing dozens of yellow balloons. The illustration of the girl is shrunk as she approaches a massive tree full of other kids on roller blades and different-coloured balloons and holding up whimsical circus tents. The elements of pale colour pop poetically against the white background and the black ink drawings. The text asks: “Do you see—how with each mistakeshe is becoming?”\r
A celebration of creativity and the possibilities for inspiration presented with each mistake.""" ;
    ns2:title "Book of Mistakes" ;
