    ns2:datePublished "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Archaia"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Roman Taylor, a teenager, must manage the family farm while his father is absent. He’s working the fields when Jet Jones, a robot boy with a jetpack, crashes into his barn while being pursued by a giant robot. Roman saves Jet, who then stays to help on the farm. Many unknown details contribute to the tension and mystery: Where is Roman’s dad? Why are so many of the kids disabled? What is Jet’s history?\r
Though the text is limited, some clues are offered: “That kid’s got history,” Roman’s elderly neighbour warns of Jet. He tells Roman about the war, which increasingly used robots to fight: “It became a war of technology, a war of secrets and lies.”\r
Much of the story is told through the sepia-toned illustrations. The browns and yellows lend a nostalgic old-fashioned feel, while the technologically advanced robots suggest that the story takes place in the future. The panels are small and action-packed; the robots are rendered in great detail, with contrasting blurry backgrounds.\r
The final panels show another huge and aggressive robot heading toward Roman’s farm while he works in the barn to revive a Model-C, a robot left over from the war which he thinks will help save the farm. It’s a riveting first volume of a four-volume series that will likely unveil its accumulated mysteries at its own calculated pace.""" ;
