ns2:Book87f159d1-7348-4752-ab50-221790cfde11 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "David Levithan" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53976" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2006"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The thrills and agonies of teenage romance and sexuality are conveyed in a furious torrent, in this lively and articulate he saidshe said account of one eventful night in New York City.\r
Alternating chapters present the different perspectives of 18-year-olds Nick and Norah, whose love of punk music brings them into each other’s orbit. An exciting setting and rich backstories are packed into this fast-paced plot of urban adventure. Insights into messy breakups and the vulnerability of new love are beautifully articulated in the voices of prickly yet fervent Norah (“God, he made great playlists for her. Tal’s mixes for me were all Dylan and Yma Sumac crap”) and artistic Nick: “‘I don’t know if I’m ready for this’ … Being open. Being hurt. Liking. Not being liked … ‘Norah. I don’t know if I’m ready for Norah.’”\r
The idea of finding a creative outlet for one’s feelings is reflected in the abundance of alternative bands cited through the tale, and in Nick’s own songwriting.\r
A range of sexualities are portrayed through the story’s varied cast of characters, including a gender-bending performer and Norah’s parents—still a devoted couple after 25 years. The fluidity of sexual preference is touched on through a girls’ washroom kiss and Norah’s musings about Nick: “Wherever Nick’s sexuality lies (lays?—whatever, same diff), the bottom line is … He’s given me more adventure and confusion in one night than I’ve had in a lifetime.” Altogether, this novel offers a witty, insightful and artfully conveyed portrait of teenage love.""" ;
