    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This hilarious, clever and entertaining adventure centres on Marcus, an intelligent worm, and Laurence, a dim-witted bird (who looks like a chicken but is convinced he’s a flamingo.) To avoid being eaten, Marcus engages Laurence in conversation, which leads to a plan to help Laurence fly to Kenya.\r
The simple black, white and pink illustrations pair with the text for multi-layered absurdity. When packing for travel, Marcus asks if there will be toilets along the way. Laurence replies: “I don’t know! I’d better take my own toilet.” The accompanying drawing shows Laurence laden with items including an electric fan, dresser drawers—and his toilet.\r
Soon after setting out, Marcus loses the map and falls from Laurence’s back, leading to an interesting discovery. The illustration shows a series of transmission towers while Marcus exclaims: “The Eiffel Tower! We’re in Paris.” After nearly being eaten by a mole, a crow and a squirrel, the pair find themselves in a place akin to Kenya, with giraffes, hippos and flamingos (where Laurence realizes he’s not what he thought.) He soon discovers he’s at the zoo, only a few minutes from home.\r
Though they don’t go far, Marcus and Laurence have many adventures and form an uncanny bond: “If Laurence hadn’t met me, he would probably be still at home, sitting on his sofa like a blob of mashed potatoes and thinking about his dreams but not doing anything about them.”""" ;
