ns2:Book88ab31ec-8d94-4316-be4b-b7240d3368fa a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Matthew McElligott" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56411" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Bloomsbury ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The lion invites the ant to dinner, along with a host of other animals. She is timid, and wishes to be polite, so she arrives exactly on time. The others all arrive late. Surprised, she watches as each of the other guests displays bad manners: the elephant talks only about himself; the hippo never wipes her mouth; the gorilla throws food; the warthog eats the centrepiece. But when the cake come out, tensions rise. The lion hands it to the elephant, asking him to help himself. The elephant takes half, and passes it on; the hippo does the same. By the time the cake reaches the ant, it is too small to divide any further. She begs the lion’s pardon, and offers to bring him a homemade cake tomorrow. The other animals scramble to top this gesture, doubling the offer every time (two cakes, four cakes, eight cakes), until the elephant finds himself promising to bring “Two hundred and forty-six peanut-butter pound cakes!’ ‘Two hundred and fifty-six,’ corrected the tortoise. ‘Oh for goodness’ sake,’ cursed the elephant.” \r
This introductory discussion of division and multiplication is brought to life with a raucous collection of animal characters in a fable that calls for good manners: “The elephant looked at the cake. ‘I could eat this in one bite,’ he thought, ‘but that might seem greedy. With a grand gesture, he cut the cake in half and passed the rest to the hippo. ‘What a pig,’ thought the hippo. But if he is taking half, I’m taking half of what’s left.’” Vivid illustrations use bold outline and watercolour-effect fills to create the animal characters in minimal background settings. This approach allows for expressive portrayal of the story’s emotional undercurrents—and detailed depictions of the cake’s division, followed by the multiplication of cakes promised for tomorrow. One page is covered in a yellow and green wash, as the tiny beetle figure (in top-hat) pops in from the bottom edge. The long tail of a speech bubble trails to the top, showing two double-chocolate fudge cakes, side by side (“I would like to bake you two cakes”). The facing page contrasts with a wash in blue and pink, as the dapper tree frog hangs from the top edge. His speech-bubble descends, showing a tidy array of raspberry layer cakes (“four… that’s twice as many.”) Much appreciated is the lyric imagination behind the cake recipes (the warthog promises to make mud cakes; the gorilla offers banana crumb cakes), and lively dialogue that invites a variety of voices when reading aloud: “‘Typical ant,’ said the elephant. ‘She thinks only of herself. When the cake came to me, I shared it. ‘I know,’ said the hippo. ‘We all did.’” A charming finish also offers a display of good manners, showing the ant and the lion at table, as he cuts her gift (a strawberry sponge cake) into even halves: “‘Such a fine cake,’ said the lion. ‘Won’t you share it with me?’” For additional math discussion, back material shows the lion’s cake, reduced by fractions, with dotted outlines on the serving plate to show their relations to the original whole.""" ;
