ns2:Book898855a7-e665-47f6-8f37-bfaa7ffe12fc a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Frieda Elizabeth & Wishinsky MacLeod" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56868" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Orca Book Publishers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This overview of activists and activism introduces middle-grade readers to a number of activists in different fields. The book is organized according to the different ways activists often come into their own, with titles like “Find your Passion,” “Be an Expert” and Be Flexible.” The chapters show the many ways we can learn to “make the world a better place” just as the subjects of these short biographies have. Some of the featured activists are well known, such as Greta Thunberg and Ai Weiwei, while others, like Minerva Hamilton Hoyt, whose work led to the founding of the Joshua Tree National Monument, may be less famous. Some have led change from within institutions, like Jacinda Ardern, the prime minister of New Zealand Aotearoa, while others, such as water protector Autumn Peltier, have worked largely independently. The activists hail from all over the world and have made changes in areas as varied as children’s rights, LGBTQ+ rights, the climate crisis, landmine and weapons awareness, women’s rights, victim support, Civil Rights and antiracism, and access to medical care, among others. The book concludes with a short list of suggestions for readers to take up their own causes based on the chapter titles, an extensive glossary, and suggested print, film and online resources, as well as an afterword from each of the authors. \r
\r
With bright backgrounds and insets, the illustrations convey the diversity of the featured activists—their ages, origins, ethnicities, cultures and genders. A colourful page prefaces each chapter, some with busy photomontages that conflate the causes of the various activists that will be discussed. The images also include archival materials and symbolic items, such as loudspeakers. Other chapters, which focus more narrowly on a single activist, include photographs that evoke what is being fought for: for instance, a chapter on environmental activist Severn Cullis-Suzuki opens on a shot of crashing waves, evergreen forests, and a looming cliff on Haida Gwaii. Colourful inset boxes provide asides, quotes and more information on people who have changed the world.""" ;
    ns2:title "How to Become an Accidental Activist" ;
