    ns2:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Trevor’s coach warns him that if he continues taking needless penalties, he will be benched. Bigger than most of the boys in his league, Trevor knows he has to change his rough, aggressive ways on the ice. A chance meeting with his favourite hockey player, Tim Horton, changes everything. Horton gives him a few practical tips on how to use his size wisely and urges him to practise daily. After he curbs his temper and improves his game enough to become “tournament all-star on defense,” Trevor credits his idol, whose sound advice taught him “how to play hockey the right way.”\r
Set in 1962, the book uses the vocabulary of hockey to seamlessly weave the parallel narratives of the boy who leads his team to victory and the celebrated hockey player who leads the Toronto Maple Leafs to their Stanley Cup win. \r
Realistic full-colour illustrations help bring the game to life. Hockey aficionados will appreciate the detailed biography at the end.\r
This one of a series of hockey-themed picture books by the author promotes skill over violence in sports. It is also an excellent introduction to the co-founder of the popular restaurant chain.""" ;
