ns2:Book8cf3877e-484f-41df-b256-40ccf0e59f00 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Lorina Mapa" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53607" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Conundrum Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This graphic memoir is a moving tribute to a daughter’s love for her father, as well as for her home country of the Philippines. After her beloved father’s sudden death, Rina gets on a plane from Montréal to Manila. Her journey plunges her into an ocean of memories from her youth in the 1980s.\r
As her personal memories flood to the surface, so do those of the context in which she grew up. From pop culture references to Depeche Mode or Duran Duran, to the revolution that overthrew the Marcos regime, to an exploration of religion in the Philippines.\r
Composed in a frank, direct and wry tone that effortlessly brings readers into Rina’s experiences, the vivid writing gives life to the political, cultural and social context of the time: “Before the world witnessed the events of China’s Tiananmen Square, Filipino nuns placed themselves on the front lines and said the rosary as they faced down tanks. While all this was going on, safe in our gated village of Ayala Alabang, Tonton was in a foul mood. ‘History is being made and I’m stuck here with the babies!’”\r
Beautifully rendered black and white panelling draws on media references, internal emotional shifts, as well as time navigation through subtle visual cues. Illustrated charts that link Rina’s cultural awakening to film, novels and music are used to great effect, illuminating her teenage years with roaring life. A 1980s discography can be found at the back.\r
An intense, humorous and highly readable memoir about growing up and becoming whole.""" ;
