ns2:Book8d2e5138-de29-4f0f-afae-18e9ee3cafee a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Juana Martinez-Neal" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56811" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This moving book introduces a young Indigenous girl’s animal friends to raise awareness of deforestation. Zonia is a little Asháninka girl who lives with her mother and her baby brother in the heart of the Amazon rainforest. Every day she hears the call of the forest, and she answers, walking through the trees and among the animals she loves, each of which are lightly, tenderly anthropomorphized: the two-toed sloths are her “old friends,” a family of Andean cocks-of-the-rock are “chatty new neighbors,” while a red-railed boa constrictor twisted around a branch invites Sonia to “see the world in new ways.” She even goes for a ride on a jaguar’s back. But one day, on her way back to her mama and baby brother, the little girl comes across a burned-out clearing. The violence done to her home frightens her, until with her mother’s help she understands that this warning too is the call of the forest. “Then I will answer,” she asserts, “as I always do.” The book concludes with an Asháninka translation of the text, a brief overview of the Asháninka people, the names of Zonia’s animal friends, further resources and facts about the Amazon River basin, including ecological threats and an excerpt from the United Nations Indigenous and Tribal Peoples Convention. \r
The accompanying illustrations were created in acrylic, coloured pencil, pastel, ink and linocut on banana bark paper handmade by women artisans. The rugged-looking textured beige background creates a tactile, earthy atmosphere, and the warm tones of the palette, with browns and the animals’ spots of bright orange, blue and red bring the sensory aspects of the Amazon basin to life. Zonia is smiling and relatable, and her world, from the ever-present blue morpho butterfly to the friendly band of coatis, is inviting, bright and safe. The family wears simple, traditional clothes, and when the little girl is empowered to tackle the environmental threat she sees, she paints her face with the lines and dots of tribal markings made from achiote.""" ;
