    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54442" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Pip wants to play. So does Nico. But their understanding of what that means is a little different. In this tuneful tale, a cuddly pig approaches an equally huggable bear with game ideas. “Do you want to play ball?” Pip asks, tossing a baseball in Nico’s direction. “Not so much,” Nico replies, happily plucking the strings of his cello. “Let’s play blocks?” Pip offers. “No, thanks,” Nico answers, smiling ear to ear. Totally absorbed by his music, Nico swings his bow in the air, knocking over the castle poor Pip has just built.\r
Watercolour and ink illustrations are minimalist and cute, keeping the tone light. A white background includes few details, making Pip and Nico the main event as Pip continues to propose fun games—heroes, detectives, magicians, explorers—all of which Nico refuses. “You’re not even looking for me!” Pip shouts, growing more and more frustrated as he tries to instigate a game of hide and seek. “Come on and play!”\r
The issue finally comes to a head when Nico counters, “I am playing . . . cello.” This fully unleashes Pip’s anger; his comeback soars across the page, swelling in font size: “I meant play with me!!!”\r
Kids will smile over the clever conclusion, a frolicsome reminder that playing music, as implied by the expression, is by nature a playful act, which can be enjoyed alone or in a group. Handing Pip a drum, Nico says, “Now we can play . . . TOGETHER!”""" ;
    ns2:title "Play With Me!" ;
