ns2:Book943a1acc-b1d1-45d1-bcb2-b60a7580126d a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Lisa Mantchev" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53294" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A little boy with a tiny elephant for a pet feels like he can “never quite fit in.” On the way to Pet Club Day, his contemplative elephant balks at the cracks in the sidewalk, so the little boy lifts him over, because “that’s what friends do: lift each other over the cracks.” But when they turn up at the club’s door there is a bold red sign that reads: “STRICTLY NO ELEPHANTS.”\r
The dejected pair come across a little girl with a pet skunk who was also not invited in: “‘The sign didn’t mention skunks,’ the girl says, ‘but they don’t want us to play with them either.’” So they decide to start their own club and make sure it is inclusive. The sweet message uses a soft, reflective tone to effortlessly teach what good friends do.\r
Illustrations use linoleum block prints, pencil and Photoshop to create a retro feel. The muted palette of green, teal, orange and brown adds to the vintage flavour. One particularly striking spread shows the little boy and his tiny elephant walking through blue-toned streets, devoid of other colours, as the rain falls; only the boy, the girl and their pets stand out in vivid tones.\r
Eventually, children from all ethnic backgrounds fill the pages, with pets from penguins to porcupines to bats. Together, they paint a friendly sign on their treehouse club: “ALL ARE WELCOME.”""" ;
