    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Phaidon"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Toto loves apples, but he’s a small worm on the ground and the apple he wants is up high in a tree. A resourceful worm, he paints a stick pink to look like a worm and, when a bird comes to get it, he climbs onto its back. Unfortunately, the bird lands in the wrong tree.\r
The gouache illustrations are sparse, with simple shapes and no shading. Toto is a thick pink line with fuchsia stripes, while the trees are yellow, textureless slabs with smooth green circles. When the bird lands in the tree, Toto’s face pokes out of a swath of green while the bird on the opposite page brings the stick worm to her chicks. To attract a squirrel who might bring Toto to the right tree, Toto paints his face red to look like a berry. The minimal text sports only a few short sentences per page: “Toto waits.Toto hangs on tight.Toto dashes off . . .. . . to the top of the tree.”\r
When a little girl named Didi arrives with her mother and a ladder, Toto watches as they pick his beloved apple and Didi takes a bite. When a plane passes in the sky, Didi drops the apple and “Toto knows that it’s now or never.” He crawls inside the apple. The final illustration shows Toto and the apple inside Didi’s stomach, together at last: “Toto is happy.” \r
A simple story about going for what you want despite obstacles along the way.""" ;
