    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Firefly Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This counting book features every number from 1 to 20, then increases in 10s all the way up to 100, using a wide range of creatures to illustrate each number. Each animal is named, and often the illustrations show a variety of species. “Three Foxes” features a red fox, a kit fox and an arctic fox. The number eight features wildly contrasting salamanders, one with brilliant green and black markings, one bright red with black dots, another blue with yellow dots. \r
\r
The paintings are incredibly detailed and realistic with a palette that varies depending on the animal. The seahorses are all brown with detailed ridges along their bodies, while the frogs on the opposite page are all different colours, sizes and shapes, ranging from the common toad to flashy yellow and orange tree frogs. \r
\r
As the digits near 100, the species aren’t as varied. Forty red shrimp are stacked in vertical lines, 70 brown mice are scattered across the page, and 90 identical penguins swim horizontally. The number 100 features tropical fish of four different species swimming in different directions, creating an underwater ocean scene. The illustrations are so detailed, this book invites not only counting but discussion about different species and the adaptability of various colours, markings and body shapes.""" ;
