ns2:Book98a26168-256a-4e44-9681-03ed5f5701b2 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Laurie Lawlor" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56527" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Holiday House Publishing"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book about a fallen tree explores the nature of community connections. “Big Tree” is a neighbourhood fixture, an old deciduous tree around which everyone gathers, for “sharing secrets, leaning and dreaming.” Everyone knows the one: “‘Meet me at Big Tree!’ we told one another. Everyone knew where to go.” The story follows what happens when a windstorm cracks the tree one day: the first-person narrator’s father calls 9-1-1, the police come, then the hydro workers and the forestry department. The fallen wires are repaired and the branches, trunk, and stump cut up and chipped. When the power is still out at nightfall, the entire neighbourhood gathers to grill and share a meal (“Don’t want to waste good ice cream”). Big Tree is transformed into firewood, mulch, a carving, and trunk sections that are perfect for sitting on. Eventually, a new sapling is planted, with the same familiar draw: “‘Meet me at Little Tree,’ we told one another. Everyone knew where to go.” \r
\r
The blockish colour illustrations of the two-page spreads show realistic representations of the big tree, its fall, the cleanup, and the aftermath. Big Tree embodies democratic multi-use of public space: it is large enough for a soccer game to take place under its canopy, for dogs to chase each other, for a family to lounge on a blanket, for a man reading and for two people calling to each other from either side of the trunk. The scenes showing the various work crews who intervene are full of the kinds of vehicles and machinery that are captivating to young readers. The other community moments—gathering on a stoop watching water crews fix the hydrant the falling tree knocked over, everyone eating outdoors by candlelight while the power is still out, people using the tree’s by-products—show a multi-ethnic neighbourhood that values togetherness.""" ;
