    ns2:datePublished "1992"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Fitzhenry___Whiteside ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Xiao Sheng works hard cutting grass and selling it to earn enough money to support himself and his mother. Despite difficulties, he always remains positive: “Who knows what the gods have in store for us. Today may not be the same as yesterday.” One day, during a terrible drought, he discovers a patch of “rich, green grass” and beneath it, a magic pearl. The pearl multiplies his family’s rice and coins and anything it touches. When Xiao Sheng swallows it to protect the gem from intruders, he is transformed into a dragon that brings the rains.\r
Pages are bordered along the bottom with a traditional Chinese pattern to frame the text. Lushly textured oil paintings sit above the writing. Scenes bathed in golden tones mainly depict landscapes and work in the fields. Occasionally, real objects are placed in the images – a coin, a pearl or a fishhook in vivid contrast to the painted illustrations.\r
The narrative is in the third person, with a densely layered text rich in folkloric and cultural motifs. Tone is imbued with the rhythms and language of folklore: “In the faraway days of cloud-breathing dragons, there lived a boy named Xiao Sheng who loved to sing.”\r
A beautifully crafted and well-told story that celebrates ancient Chinese culture, this book includes a fascinating appendix at the back about dragons and their mythology.""" ;
