ns2:Book9c267092-a6b2-4bd9-860a-62877609d0fb a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Minh Lê" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54619" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "DisneyHyperion Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This story symbolically moves from wordlessness to language, as an Asian-American boy is forced to visit his old-world grandfather. Comics-style illustrations depict the despondent boy and his ecstatic grandfather—greeting each other, sharing a meal, watching TV—each locked inside his own language.\r
Artwork uses warm hues in watercolour effects to create the pair’s highly expressive faces and body language. A wonderful bird’s-eye composition depicts mealtime, while portraying their cross-cultural challenge: Grandfather’s hands set his bowl of noodle soup on the table, between chopsticks and a spoon; the boy’s hands patiently wait to start digging into his lunch of hot dog, salad and fries.\r
\r
Our ability to communicate despite language barriers is dramatically demonstrated when the boy pulls out his drawing markers, and the grandfather responds with his brush and ink: “Right when I gave up on talking, my grandfather surprised me by revealing a world beyond words.” Panel art depicting homey scenes transforms into full-page images of superhero rampages. The pair’s respective alter-egos create richly detailed and wondrous landscapes, but a magic chasm emerges between them—old man on one side, boy on the other.\r
\r
The idea of exchange culminates in the heroes’ battle against the dragon that emerges from the chasm, with the boy wielding his grandfather’s brush-staff and the old man taking up the child’s marker: “Now after years of searching for the right words, we find ourselves happily . . . speechless.”""" ;
