    ns2:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Peachtree Publishers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Catkin leaps off Amy’s lap to go hunting. But although the little yellow cat hears his prey—the “kerik-kerik” of Cricket, the “garrump. Garrump” of Frog—and glimpses “a long tail “of Mouse and the stripes of Snake, each time he leaps, he finds nothing: “Mouse jumps through a crack in the shed. Where is Mouse?” Catkin tries to search for his elusive prey up a tree and gets stuck there, mewling for his human until Amy climbs the tree to retrieve him, at which point his emphatic “Meeeow” turns to “Purrrrrrrrrr.” The animal calls beg to be read out loud, and the simple sentences evoke the coil and pounce of the cat’s foiled attempts at hunting. The use of rhythm and repetition are aurally engaging, while the elaborate illustrations conceal a number of animals, encouraging readers to spot them.\r
Each small white section of text is framed and bordered in sunny yellow—nearly the only spots of white in the whole book. The intricately detailed, bright and layered illustrations are reminiscent of Slavic or medieval decoration, all filigree, curlicue and concentric loops. Each two-page spread includes a border, either framing or dividing the images into panels, depicting yellow animal silhouettes against a red background. Narratively, the illustrations show Catkin becoming more and more discomfited by his failed hunt. There are many delightful secondary details, like an owl nestled in a hole in the tree peering up at Amy as she climbs from one branch to another.""" ;
