ns2:Book9d1d0e4f-8f67-417f-956b-ad4a4e0a83b2 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jonny Lambert" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54547" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Tiger Tales"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Mouse is scampering through the dark forest when there is a “horrible howl.” Mouse meets Owl on a tree branch; Owl asks, “Hoo-hoo, was that you?” Then Bear climbs the tree to ask, “Which one of you made that awful AAA-OOO?” More and more animals join them and they begin to imagine the “monster” responsible for the howl. “Monsters eat everything!” says Duck with a cry. “We’ll be plucked, stuffed, and roasted, and put in a pie!”\r
In a moment of panic, the animals begin climbing the tree to escape the monster. The tree “creaked, shuddered, and groaned” until ultimately, “CRACK!” The animals tumble to the ground. As they fall, they cry out. Owl goes “HOOT.” Mouse goes “SQUEAK.” Wolf goes “AAA-OOO.” Once they realize that it was Wolf who howled because he was “alone in the dark, lonely woods,” all the animals fall asleep together. At least until the rooster crows.\r
The rhyming text offers a catchy rhythm and plenty of amusing animal sounds: “Duck, Goose, and Dove landed with a startled QUACK, HONK, and COO!” The light-coloured digital illustrations on a stark black background have sleek contours that almost look like cut and paste. Each animal features a different colour and faint-textured pattern: Bear is yellowy-brown with a wood-like texture while Goose is white and yellow with circular patterns.""" ;
