ns2:Book9eb8c136-e8a3-460c-803b-f485ce5e44ad a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Amanda Lovelace" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54099" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Andrews McMeel"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This collection of poems offers a trenchant examination of patriarchy’s oppression of women—in history and today. Drawing on symbolism derived from historic witch hunts and fairy tales, brief poems convey anger, fear and women’s suffering under current gender politics, while conjuring up images of feminine power and healing: “sipthe silky elixirfrom my cupped palms … untilthe lovebecomes sosecond natureyou need itno more.here,we’ll drink together.bottoms up.–self-love potion.”\r
Direct, incisive language upbraids the hypocrisies, contradictions and threat of violence women face every day, such as in the poem-pair “how to prevent getting sexually assaulted” (showing an empty item-list, covered in scribbles) and “how to prevent sexually assaulting someone,” showing a list of one item, repeated over and over: “don’t rape. don’t rape. don’t rape.”\r
Free verse, prose-poems, list-poems and poems using expressive type and layout offer a variety of inspiring writing models. Literary references include works such as The Handmaid’s Tale, Wintergirls and The Hunger Games. Poems such as “things i still struggle to say & that’s okay” and “i’m not ashamed to say i’m my first priority” offer insight into the complexities of internalized oppression.\r
Altogether, this collection offers a raging gift to readers of all genders who would explore the use of symbol to examine social issues and strike out for better ways: “sit up & pay attentionas i take your name drag it through the very flamesyou built.”""" ;
    ns2:title "Witch Doesn't Burn in This One" ;
