ns2:Booka5923218-1755-4741-8718-ba19f19e131a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Sara Levine" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54907" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Lerner"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody "This book compares the bony appendages of various vertebrates, from snakes to whales to ungulates, by comically raising the question of what humans would look like with or without particular skeletal structures. For instance, “what kind of animal would you be if you had really big vertebrae in your neck?” Each riddle leads not only to the answer, overleaf, but to some information about the animal in question. In this case, we learn that each vertebra in a giraffe’s neck can be more than 25 centimetres long. The language straddles accessibility and lexical accuracy, juxtaposing scientifically accurate terminology—“the spine,” for instance—with more colloquial terms—“or backbone.” The question and answer format used to illustrate aspects of vertebrate skeletal structure invites participation, and also highlights the animal nature of humans: “What if your vertebrae didn’t stop at your rear end,” the book asks next to an illustration of a little boy glancing back at his tail. The full-page colour drawings playfully skew proportion and rejig anatomical accuracy, appending a bat’s wing to a little girl’s arm in one image, and in another showing the difficulty of grasping a cup of juice with only two fingers, like cloven hooves. The book also alludes to the class of invertebrates (“Could you be an animal if you didn’t have any bones at all?”) with an enjoyably gross boneless puddle of child. Additional data and a short glossary conclude the book." ;
    ns2:title "Bone by Bone: Comparing Animal Skeletons" ;
