    ns2:datePublished "2005"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Sleeping Bear Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """What could be more topical for children than an alphabet book about school? With headings such as “History,” “Quizzes” and “Secretary,” readers are taken on an alphabet tour through 26 words connected with this most familiar of places. \r
Each letter features a short rhyming verse (“Gymnasium begins with G.We show up there to have P.E.,a class that keeps us toned and trimand teaches us to lose and win”) as well as a lengthier sidebar that provides additional information for more capable readers. The large, detailed illustrations capture the essence of life of school A series of custodians, both male and female, “paint and patch and fix” things, with the ubiquitous hefty set of keys depicted on the side. A crossing guard with a bright yellow coat and large blue umbrella helps children cross the street on a rainy day.\r
Specific to the Canadian context, with references to provincial governments, the maple leaf on the flag and Canada’s Food Guide, the book reflects the multicultural diversity of today’s schools. The book finishes with a simple short quiz, the answers to which can be found throughout the book.""" ;
