ns2:Booka9a4cc51-23b5-4c2e-b0b2-af92123a0eec a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kevin Luthardt" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52855" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Peachtree Publishers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Edgar has a nice life. He loves his best friend, Quincy, with whom he does everything. When Edgar and his parents move to a new town, everything seems scary and different. The kids at his new school “look weird” and dress “funny.” They listen to “bizarre music” and eat “strange food.” Not only that, the “biggest, weirdest kid” keeps staring at him and follows him everywhere. What does he want with Edgar?\r
Simple text relies on colloquial speech and short sentences to relate the emotional upheaval children face when they are uprooted and taken to live in a new, unfamiliar place. The never-judge-a-book-by-its-cover theme will be readily apparent to most read-aloud audiences. \r
Bold, acrylic artwork features bright colours, cartoonish monsters with dramatic eyeballs, tentacles and antennae, and alien landscapes of curvy dwellings. \r
What differentiates this story from others about moving and having to adjust to new surroundings is that, rather than humans, the characters are robots and aliens—an instant appeal factor.""" ;
