    ns2:datePublished "1967"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Beginning with “Brown Bear, Brown Bear, What do you see? I see a red bird looking at me,” each double-page spread in this classic read-aloud showcases a colourful, collaged animal and a simple, rhythmic text that propels readers to the next page. The bear announces the red bird, who, in turn, announces the yellow duck, and so on, until the final question, in which the teacher asks, “Children, Children, What do you see?” which is followed by the last page, on which every animal from the story is reproduced with its name and colour (e.g. blue horse, green frog, purple cat) printed below it. Early readers will want to join in this rhythmic chant from first page to last.\r
Bright, eye-catching illustrations, rhyming narrative and a repetitive sentence structure make this an excellent choice for children just beginning to learn their words, colours and animals. It also serves as an effective confidence booster for emergent readers, and as a basic introduction to poetry.""" ;
