ns2:Bookac6b5343-60d4-426d-b6db-ebeb18d240b4 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Thao Lam" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54625" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Owlkids ;
    ns2:reviewBody """No two families are quite alike. That’s the lesson to learn from this hilarious picture book. Busting the nuclear family stereotype, pets are portrayed as full-fledged family members in lieu of children. “My cat looks like my dad,” the story begins. “They both love milk. And sardines. Ewwww.”\r
Beyond physical appearances (both the cat and his dad boast bright blue eyes and a generous golden mane), the feline’s routines and preferences make him a regular chip off the old block. “My cat and my dad always start their mornings with stretches,” reads a side-splitting spread. As the reader realizes that dad’s calisthenics poses are strikingly similar to cat stretches, unassuming text, paired with campy cut-out illustrations, is delivered like a punchline. “And their afternoons with naps,” the narrator continues. Meanwhile, Dad’s late-seventies workout wear, replete with head- and wristbands, triggers extra titters as he and the cat are shown passing out on the couch.\r
Readers will roar with laughter over the surprise ending. Up until the final pages, one assumes the story is narrated by the dad’s child. “Yup, my cat looks like my dad. And me? I look like my mom,” teases the storyteller. “We both have wild hair. Our eyes are the same color. And we both love to dance!” Flipping through the last pages, readers discover that the narrator is in fact a pet bird: “Family is what you make it,” the bird concludes, acknowledging diversity.""" ;
    ns2:title "My Cat Looks Like My Dad" ;
