    ns2:datePublished "2007"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simply_Read_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Exquisite watercolour paintings are a highlight in this rustic story about a boy who greets the dawn with binoculars. Honouring family and nature, equally poetic text celebrates the glory of a new day: “The first morning rays streamed into the children’s room and danced on Patrick’s pillow.”\r
As Patrick crawls out of bed, his sister stirs. “‘Where are you going?’ she mumbled, yawning. ‘To look for loons,’ whispered Patrick.” Thanks to Patrick’s binoculars, readers get to zoom in on nature’s gems: frogs, dragonflies and chipmunks are stunning amid the pinecones and golden trees lining the lake.\r
As the rest of the family rises, the text teems with onomatopoeia, making it perfect for reading aloud. “‘Tweet,’ went the whistle of the brass kettle,” signalling Grandma’s presence in the kitchen.\r
Each family member adds to the morning’s music, until everybody is up. Meanwhile, text and visuals ensure that all the reader’s senses are, in turn, awakened. One can almost taste the feast “Dad” prepares in the kitchen. Yet, even as the family sits down to breakfast, Patrick resists “the smell of sizzling bacon and pancakes” drifting past the porch. He’s determined to see a loon.\r
Patrick’s patience pays off when a family of loons glides into view, harmonizing with the cheerful clatter of his own clan: “‘Smack,’ went one bird as it dove deep into the water. ‘Caooooooom,’ went another, calling out to its family.""" ;
