ns2:Bookaccd6650-25d9-42f9-822e-7e12ce89c42c a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "John Lewis" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53273" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Top Shelf Productions"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Through shifts back and forth in time, US Congressman John Lewis recalls his childhood on a sharecropper farm and his early years fighting segregation through non-violent resistance.\r
Vivid personal anecdotes are conveyed, including a tense account of the dangers of simply driving through southern states. “Uncle Otis … knew which places offered ‘colored’ bathrooms—and which were safer to just pass on by.” Memories are presented in context with key events that sparked the demand for black civil rights in 1960s USA, such as the murder of Emmett Till, the sham trial of his racist killers and Rosa Parks’ stand in Montgomery, Alabama.\r
Monochrome artwork makes good use of composition, tone and brushstroke to depict the underlying emotions of every scene. One page shows a childhood escape from farm work, through a stack of wide panels: the distant school bus, John’s dash across his father’s field, his leap through the bus door and a final panoramic view of the land, as the dwarfed bus takes him away.\r
Of special interest is the book’s inside-perspective on training for non-violent sit-ins and marches. The protesters’ rejection of racist mores, policing and the justice system has a mighty effect, as shown in the inspirational ending. Final scenes depict continued action for desegregation, under dialogue balloons spoken by Martin Luther King, Jr.: “No lie can live forever.… Walk together children. Don’t get weary.”""" ;
