ns2:Bookae61254b-05e0-4f61-82a4-438539fc0962 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "John Martz" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53775" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Koyama Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This wordless story collection is full of quirky humour and animal protagonists. On one page, Doug and Mouse are going on an adventure. The two-page digital illustration features the pair in various situations as they travel down a winding river in a small motor boat: Doug reads a map while Mouse stares at a crocodile; Doug peers through binoculars while Mouse consults a bird book. Finally, they take a nap—as their boat nears a waterfall. \r
The illustrations are simple in shape, with a subdued palette and solid colours. While the objects themselves are simple, each scene is rich with details, inviting the reader to linger and discover the multiple narratives in each scene. On another two-page spread, Tim the cat is playing mini golf. In each panel we see the ball approaching the hole, but as the ball reaches the hole, water spurts out. On the opposite page, we see that Tim is actually standing on a giant whale. \r
In the final chapter, an elderly porcine couple sits on a bench. Each page presents the same scene, but the colours change to show night, then autumn and winter. The red bird in the tree above changes position—sleeping in one, raking leaves in another. After a year of sitting, the woman asks, “Did I leave the oven on?” The man replies, “Better check.” The next page shows their house on fire, and in the final scene, they’re back on the bench, smouldering and bewildered.""" ;
    ns2:title "A Cat Named Tim and Other Stories" ;
