    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“It’s game day. One last look. Cleats? Check.” The language of this non-fiction book cleverly portrays the setting, while leading readers to the important visual function behind the image. A soccer ball to the head (“BAM!”) provides the perfect opening to explain how muscles and fat protect the eye in its bony socket. This combination of storyline and fact is an elegant and effective way to help readers learn and retain information.\r
Hand-drawn illustrations make dexterous use of diagrams within the story: the function between the eye and light serves as the game play, which the team huddles around. This approach also allows for editorial illustration within diagrams, such as when a giant iris expands around a vision of the battling soccer teams, in response to clouds blocking the sun.\r
Sports and science enthusiasts alike will enjoy the finish, when the winning goal is kicked into the net: “. . . you never once had to tell your eyes what to do. You just had to keep them open. Your eyes and your brain are a great team.”\r
Back material offers recommendations for further research, an index, and a glossary with a wonderful and informative sketch of a giant eyeball model-construction.""" ;
