    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Lorimer"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“I’ve never really been hugged by a boy before. It makes me feel a little more like I’m really gay and not making it up.” This brief novel explores the kaleidoscopic world of gender fluidity through the voice of Grade 11 student Logan, who is starting at a new school for the performing arts (and leaving old bullies behind). Welcomed by a circle of diverse “queer” friends, Logan experiments with clothes, parties, support groups and romance, while crushing on Kyle—a straight boy in class.\r
The eventful plot incorporates a range of gender- and sexual-orientations (“I just don’t know what kind of not-guy I am. Maybe I’m genderqueer or non-binary?”) while shining a spotlight on restrictive aspects of mainstream, cis-gendered society—epitomized by Logan’s own mixed-heritage Chinese-Canadian family.\r
Throughout the journey of self-discovery, Logan must sift through racist and sexist constructs (“This guy is hitting on me. That means I’m not ugly for being an effeminate Asian stereotype . . . right?”) while questioning his own devotion to the unavailable—and now oddly behaving—Kyle. In a satisfying finish, a self-transformed Logan is now calling ‘themself’ Veronica: “I have makeup on, courtesy of a trip with Jennifer to Nyx Cosmetics. I travelled all the way to Sherbourne like this without becoming the newest statistic for the Trans Day of Remembrance. So yay progress.” Thanks to a push from a friend, an exciting romance with Kyle has begun: “Now you can both stop mooning after each other. You’re welcome. 8-)”""" ;
