    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Tuttle"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Ah Fu is a young boy who lived long ago in the countryside by the Yellow River in China. He and his family are hunter-gatherers, living off wild fruit and game. One day he finds a white horse and brings him home. Ah Fu notices a particular plant that the horse eats and his family try their hand at farming millet, but with no success. One day, the wild horse plunges into the river and returns with a drawing on his back that “shows the cycles of the changing seasons.” Learning the appropriate times to sow, water and harvest leads Ah Fu’s family and their descendants to become successful farmers.\r
This legend is told in a formal, poetic tone that echoes the rhythms of old storytelling traditions: “When the thunder roared, the animals were awakened from hibernating, and the earth turned warm, ‘it’s time to plow your fields,’ the white horse told Ah Fu.”\r
Watercolour artworks in subdued tones are painted in the style of traditional Chinese landscapes. Swirls in the clouds and lines and dots on clothing and baskets abound; the edges of the hillsides, river and fields are blurred and dreamlike.\r
After people start to farm by the seasons, they come up with the “24 Solar Terms”. These terms are outlined in a chart at the back of the book. Chinese characters above and the English translation directly below makes for a uniquely bilingual text.""" ;
