    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“We didn’t come here for the tall buildings. We didn’t come for the luxury. We came for the peace.” Afghan refugee Najeeba’s feelings recall those of Jewish boat refugee Ruth, some 60 years before: “I am not particularly interested in going to America. I am interested in staying alive.” Five personal accounts are drawn from different migrations over the past several decades. Timelines describe additional migrations from 1670 to the present—demonstrating the ubiquitous violence and persecution that creates refugees.\r
The stories include background contexts (“Mohamed handed the smuggler all his money … There was nothing left for the seventeen-year-old in Libya”) and epilogues that summarize the refugees’ assimilation into their new countries: “José was shocked by the poverty and drugs in their US neighbourhood and wondered why they’d left Cuba at all.” Key statistics and brief sidebars provide further insight: “Captains and crews are obligated under maritime law to help vessels in danger.”\r
Double-page, collage-style illustrations incorporate historic photos, artistic markings, maps and news images. One image shows a traditional fishing boat, jammed with passengers, floating on the South China Sea. A chalk-effect moon shines in a ‘blackboard’ sky. One passenger sits out on the boat’s gunwale, as markings in the water seem to count off the days on board the small vessel. (“Phu’s journey: 425 people on the boat, 17 pirate attacks, 14 days at sea, 8 months in Pulau Bidong Refugee Camp.) Altogether, this book offers a succinct and powerful synthesis of basic issues surrounding refugees and the global community.""" ;
