    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Before knowledge, there is curiosity and speculation and dreaming; and before science as we know it today, that dreaming was informed by magic and the possibility of metamorphosis. The 18 chapters of this biography introduce the man whose discoveries about light and gravity would make him one of the greatest scientists of all time. Newton’s life is traced from his lonely childhood and time as a boarder in an apothecary’s shop to his early interest in astronomy and mechanics, and his work in the “deep magic” of alchemy. During his tenure as professor of mathematics at Cambridge, Newton met astronomer Edmond Halley—a pivotal encounter, which led to the development and dissemination of Newton’s work on the motion of celestial bodies. Newton began to test his theories, and … “the door to the universe swung open.” Newton’s laws of motion would go on to form the foundation of modern physics. \r
The biography is written in compelling language and fast-paced scenes that bring Newton’s work to life. Conjectural information is filled in with tongue-in-cheek possibilities: for instance, although “no one today can know exactly how Isaac and his friends spent their time,” a list Newton drew up of his “childhood ‘sins’” refers to making mousetraps and “squirting water.” The book is illustrated with Newton’s drawings, reproductions of his manuscripts and of the frontispieces of his books, and woodcuts from the era. \r
The book also includes extensive source notes and a bibliography, as well as an index.""" ;
    ns2:title "Isaac the Alchemist: Secrets of Isaac Newton, Reveal'd" ;
