    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Balzer + Bray"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Izzy and Brianna’s narratives alternate throughout this graphic novel. Izzy’s passion is drama but she struggles with schoolwork. Brianna is known in middle school as “The Brain,” but thinks “it’d be nice to be seen past my brains.” When Izzy fails another assignment, her hard-working single mom grounds her, preventing her from participating in the talent show. And when Brianna’s mom, the drama teacher, asks her to replace an actor in the talent show, she hesitates. \r
\r
Brianna’s storyline is executed in bright full-colour panels that include dialogue, text messages and emojis. One series of panels shows her mother trying to convince her to participate in the talent show and features vibrant backgrounds with comic-style characters. Izzy’s storyline is done in a pastel palette with a white background and sketch-style drawings. One page shows an argument between Izzy and her mother with only their heads depicted: “No talent show . . . No negotiating.” \r
\r
Brianna agrees to participate, but she struggles with nerves while operating outside her comfort zone: “I’m used to feeling like everything’s gonna go my way.” Izzy sneaks out of the house while her mom is napping and is more nervous about getting caught than performing. The two narratives converge in the final scene when it’s revealed that Izzy is actually Brianna’s mother. Izzy learned to pursue her passion without jeopardizing her schoolwork, allowing her to become a drama teacher and convince her daughter, Brianna, to try acting herself. A laid-back, humorous, and entertaining story of contrasting passions and parental relationships.""" ;
