    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """As a member of the Sinclair family— “old-money Democrats”—Cadence has spent every summer on an island near Martha’s Vineyard with her cousins, Mirren and Johnny, and with Gat, the nephew of her aunt’s partner—the teens collectively known as “the Liars.” The summer they are 15, Cady is mysteriously injured. Returning to Beechwood Island two years later, she begins, with difficulty, to piece together what happened. “Silence,” her mother tells her, “is a protective coating over pain.” Little by little, Cady remembers: stories about Granddad and his three daughters, arguments, bargaining, falling in love with Gat. And the Liars’ rash and ultimately tragic plan to bring the family together.\r
The sentences are occasionally broken up over several lines, which, along with the use of repetition, suggests an adolescent breathlessness. The Liars are verbally and emotionally articulate; when Cady’s father leaves or when her grandmother dies, she describes physical injury and profuse bleeding. The writing is lightly poetic and italicized fairy tale sections, with echoes of King Lear, provide recurrent alternate narratives in which Cady can mythologize her family at a distance.\r
When the improbable surprise ending quickly ties up two years of amnesia and silence, doomed myth meets calamitous reality: “The princesses, the fathers, the king, and the children, they crumbled like eggshells, powdery and beautiful.”""" ;
