ns2:Bookb956dc34-b499-4df0-bb53-27da6826e043 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Terri Libenson" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55544" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Balzer + Bray"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Thirteen-year-old Emmie is artistic and funny, but her shyness makes speaking to classmates painfully difficult. Katie, on the other hand, is outgoing and popular. Their alternating narratives are portrayed in vastly different styles. Emmie’s features prose describing her inner world, accompanied by small drawings in a pale palette. One shows her with her head plunged into her locker wondering, “Does anyone even see me? Do I even want them to?” Katie’s world is portrayed in comic-style panels with vibrant backgrounds and dialogue. She is shown playing sports, studying, applying face cream and talking on the phone: “Some call me lucky, but I work hard for everything I have.”\r
\r
Emmie has one friend, Brianna. As a joke, they write “really gushy, sappy love notes” to their crushes, but Emmie’s note for Tyler falls into the hands of a bully. Katie is already dating Tyler, but she doesn’t see Emmie as a threat. She sticks up for Emmie when the bully starts trouble and breaks up with Tyler for failing to do so. The final pages reveal that Katie existed only in Emmie’s sketchbook as her alter-ego: “When I couldn’t say something, she said it for me.” As Emmie emerges from her shell of shyness and finds her voice, she no longer needs Katie. Tyler takes an interest in Emmie and they discover they’re both good at art. And flirting. This humorous coming of age story realistically portrays the struggles of being shy and the often-conflicting fear and desire to be seen.""" ;
