ns2:Bookb965b6fd-3457-4f3b-b864-65ecc872be21 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Joseph Lambert" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54524" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "DisneyHyperion Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The opening pages feature small black panels with a grey abstract child gesticulating, reaching, teetering, spitting and throwing things while a pair of blue arms correct, contain, and restrain. The arms are Annie Sullivan’s. While Helen Keller’s story is widely known, this rendition delves into Sullivan’s troubled past and the monumental challenge of Helen’s early education.\r
Scenes between Sullivan and Keller are interspersed with scenes from Annie’s childhood, first in the poorhouse, where she lived with her brother until he died, and later at the Perkins Institute for the Blind. The early scenes with Keller show the initial struggle to “break through” and communicate that everything has a name. Sullivan’s narrative takes the form of letters to her previous headmaster: “My most pressing challenge is to discipline her without breaking her spirit.” The panels are small, often sixteen to a page and feature a pale palette with plenty of action including chaotic wrestling scenes with black smoke rising from their heads. Occasional panels are black, illustrating Helen’s isolation, but when she finally grasps the concept of nouns, brown labeled objects appear on a black background as her world expands, gaining shape and meaning.\r
While Keller is a “tyrant” in the beginning, the more she learns, the calmer she becomes. Scenes from Sullivan’s childhood reveal that she, too, had a defiant spirit that often caused her trouble at school. These strong personalities helped them overcome extreme adversity and form a lifelong bond.""" ;
