    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53510" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Flannery first becomes famous because of her chicken, which can walk backwards. But soon, Flannery begins to feel “that life was a little too quiet.” Thinking that “more birds would do the trick,” she buys “one of every type she could find.” Still, Flannery’s life seems to lack that rush. A peacock seems the perfect answer, but her peacock only fans his spectacular tail feathers “when he feels like it,” which is to say never. Not until she thinks to introduce him to “the Queen of the Birds” does the peacock fan and strut. Eventually, the royal couple find life “still a little too quiet” and the wordless last page shows the resulting brood of peachicks.\r
The self-assured and driven protagonist drives this madcap quest for action. Larger hand-printed-style fonts are used to convey Flannery’s emphatic declarations, as when she introduces the peacock to the barnyard: “HE’S IN CHARGE NOW!” The two-page mixed-media spreads use pencil texturing, blocks of solid colour and collaged archival newsprint to depict the be-fowled yard, a night noisy with avian screeching or a picnic in honour of the king of the birds. The illustrations add a layer of irony to the narrative: the text claims the peacock is “enthused” upon his arrival, but his furrowed brow and petulance suggest otherwise.\r
An afterword reveals the inspiration for the book—the American author Flannery O’Connor and her flock of birds—and directs readers to her work, “when you are older.”""" ;
