ns2:Bookba7a0aa2-702f-407a-b854-c368ae331783 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Elly MacKay" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54241" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Running Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """When a little girl’s family moves to the city, she knows she’ll miss butterflies most of all, until she discovers a fenced area next door called Butterfly Park. Alas, it doesn’t live up to its name: there is nary a butterfly to be seen, even when the girl brings cookies (“for it was always smart to make a good first impression”). She enlists the help of her neighbours to catch some butterflies to stock the park, but when released, the butterflies fly out over the gate. Fortunately, one butterfly stays behind and leads the children through town to a garden. Aha!—the girl tries to lure butterflies to her park with a bouquet, but that doesn’t seem to work either. Before long, the entire neighbourhood tromps in, with “boots and gnomes and wagons” and “trowels and dirt and shovels”—all the necessities to make a garden home for butterflies. In time, the little girl too, feels “right at home.”\r
\r
Simple, short and elegant, the text acts as a springboard into the ornate, original illustrations. The cut-paper illustrations provide a sense of depth and movement, as when the girl leaps at monarchs with a net, or skips through the town’s narrow streets and archways. The colourful drawings-inside-drawings lend the story a filmic, timeless quality. \r
\r
The author’s website offers a behind-the-scenes glimpse of the process used to create the layers at play in the theatres of her backdrops.""" ;
