ns2:Bookbaa35227-3208-4c3d-865b-e7d784b244d2 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Rob Laidlaw" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53237" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Pajama_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The last three elephants at the Toronto Zoo were doing poorly, suffering from the northern climate and the lonely, poorly duplicated habitat. Instead of transferring them to another zoo, city officials bowed to pressure from animal-rights activists and agreed to allow them to live out their days at the PAWS sanctuary in California. Moving three four-tonne elephants across over 4000 kilometres was no easy feat: special crates were constructed; a whole caravan of people, including elephant-welfare experts, was needed. The convoy trumpeted along, weathering snowstorms and mechanical trouble, until finally Toka, Thika and Iringa reached freedom and a herd of their own.\r
The tone of this true story is compassionate without being sententious. The book nonetheless points out the impossibility of replicating natural conditions in zoos: “Every day was the same as the day before. Only the weather changed.” Representative soft earthy oil paintings provide full-page visual counterpoints to the unfolding journey.\r
The author also chronicles the grassroots process that led to the relocation of the elephants and provides an update on the three pachyderms in their new home, where they bask in the sun with “the luxury of soft grass under their feet.”\r
A substantial appendix includes elephant facts and photographs, and gives further details on the living conditions of the Toronto Zoo elephants.""" ;
