ns2:Bookc0432450-c708-4a35-bb83-f73cb2937eeb a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "David Levithan" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54928" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The organizing principle in this collection—a playlist of songs—provides the structure for a discussion of almost endless aspects of youth, such as early romantic fumblings, looking back at your parents’ relationship, figuring how to express emotions, and realizing hard truths about yourself. Each of the 19 stories is a “track,” and some are written in verse, with one of them presented as an “8-Song Memoir,” a Walkman tour of self-discovery via tunes by Everything But the Girl, Sting, Annie Lennox and Peter Gabriel, as well as other memorable songs. Many of the pieces feature LGBTQ+ characters or concerns. Several of the stories revisit characters from the author’s earlier novels, and some are non-fiction, blurring the line between recollection and invention. \r
\r
This collection compiles many stories the author was known to have been writing for his friends annually on Valentine’s Day, and the theme of love recurs. The voice is consistent across the stories—wry, punchy and contemporary—and there is an emotional bluntness that bleeds through, whether the character is playing Santa at his boyfriend’s house (“I want him to love me when I’m naughty and when I’m nice”) or whether the author is remembering a crush on an older boy in a college writing class: “The difference between a crush and a love is its viability.” Some of the cultural references date the point of view, but the book is definitely contemporary, with allusions to late twenty-tens political leaders (“Making America gay again”) and television shows, books and movies.""" ;
