ns2:Bookc29aa2be-649f-4a5a-8306-fef8a3720041 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Helen Lester" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54906" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Hmh ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In faraway Scotland, way down at the bottom of Loch Ness, lives a family of three monsters: Nessie, Fergus and “their wee laddie, Angus.” They do their best to live by the Five Basic Rules of monster etiquette. Unfortunately, Angus has a lot of trouble with “2. Always pick up after yourself.” He tosses toys and puggy-nit (peanut) shells, his lochweed collection spills out everywhere and his hummie-doddies (mittens) are all mixed up. Fed up, his parents lock him in his room, delivering a daily meal of milk and tatties-in-a-can. \r
\r
Told in a marvelous tongue-and-cheek manner, the narrative voice is full of charm and peppered with Scottish dialect. The pace is just right, building tension as Angus’s pile of muck rises so high he finally breaks through to the surface of the lake: “Surface of the loch . . . had forgotten Basic Monster Rule 1: NevereverEVER go up to the surface of the loch. But here was Angus. Rising.” \r
\r
Ink-and-watercolour illustrations match the wit and chaos of the storytelling, with fabulous renditions of monsters clad in tartan skirts, with expressive faces and toothy mouths. One image shows the junk pile in elaborate detail with bicycles, lochweed, tennis rackets, dirty dishes, balls and soft toys as Angus tumbles from the top of the heap all the way to his bedroom floor. \r
\r
The surface of the lake is so foreign and frightening that Angus learns his lesson: it’s time to clean up. He puts everything in its place and order is restored. A lovely lesson in following the rules.""" ;
