ns2:Bookc41cea93-1a0e-4cc6-9499-eaca5a3e7208 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Thao Lam" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54528" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Owlkids ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A skunk gets a bright red balloon tied to its paw, and so begins an epic journey. No one notices the little skunk at first as he is hidden in a parade of balloons, but he soon causes no end of alarm, startling zoo animals, tenants in an apartment building and drivers on a busy road. He holds his breath as he dips in to visit some concerned fish and octopuses; he floats past a waterfall and through a desert.\r
In a book that relies exclusively on its illustrations to develop character and maintain narrative progression, each scene is both part of the continuum and self-contained. In most scenes, someone is shown freaking out at the flying skunk: a man cooking in his apartment sets his pot on fire; a construction worker lunching on a suspended i-beam loses his sandwich.\r
The collages that illustrate this story juxtapose endless patterns and colours to create characters, objects and backgrounds that are at once evocatively representative and playfully trompe-l’œil. Even within relatively unified colour-blocks, such as the grey and white skunk, several textures jostle to create depth and movement. In some cases—like the rows of laundry drying on clotheslines stretched between buildings—the choice of patterns is creative and seemingly endless. \r
The skunk finally lands after hitching a ride on a Ferris wheel, but he decides he likes travelling and takes to the sky once again with a new bunch of balloons.""" ;
