ns2:Bookc688fee2-d638-4caa-9227-c27c83983c1b a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Elizabeth MacLeod" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55566" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Tom Longboat is a young Onondaga from the Six Nations Reserve. As a boy, he loves distance running and has a natural talent for the sport. He escapes from the torments of the residential school where he is sent and eventually begins to race professionally, soon coming to international attention. This biography touches on his economical running style, outlines his varied and unorthodox training regimen, and narrates major races, including the time Longboat outran a train. Although he never wins the Olympic marathon event, collapsing in the heat at the 1908 London Games, Longboat is recognized as the top marathoner in the world in his time. He is acclaimed by the Canadian public and well-liked during his service as part of the largely Indigenous 107th Pioneer Battalion. After the war, Longboat returns to Toronto to live a quiet life with his family, and eventually returns to the Six Nations Reserve. The story provides appropriate context for the culturally genocidal practices surrounding the residential school system and emphasizes the humility and self-knowledge of a man who, “most of all, just loved to run!” A timeline glossary at the end of the biography highlights Longboat’s personal and professional milestones, as well as important moments in Indigenous history and athletics. \r
\r
The cartoonish watercolour and ink illustrations make a bygone era and a solitary sport attractive and accessible to young readers and embed the achievements of an Indigenous athlete visually as well as narratively in the national consciousness. As well as paragraphs of text, each page features speech or thought bubbles that provide additional insight and liveliness (for instance, as four runners line up in the shadow of the Tower of London, each is nervous about some aspect of the race, from running on cobblestones—“they’re so bumpy”—to the oppressive heat, to being monarchy-shy).""" ;
