ns2:Bookc90fdd2d-21c3-4bc8-978b-bcc2c9949758 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jenny Manzer" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53648" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Sadness is all 15-year-old Nico can remember. Her mother disappeared when she was four, young enough to have retained a handful of memories that serve as both comfort and torment. Her mother’s absence weighs heavily on Nico, who lives with her gentle yet absent father. An outsider at school, Nico is one of the “weird kids.” Her only friend is Obe, and together they feed their lonely souls with music.\r
Nico’s increasing obsession with her missing mother overlaps with her obsession with Kurt Cobain. When Nico sees a man on the ferry whom she thinks is Cobain, in an act of desperation, she hides in the backseat of his car, thus igniting an action-filled quest to discover the truth about her mother.\r
The language is beautiful and original throughout, with literary descriptions and clever similes: “Snowdrops are a sad kind of flower, because sometimes, like the robins, they come back too soon. They think it’s spring, so they nudge out, only to be smacked down by another frost.”\r
The narrative maintains a satisfying blend of introspection, action, mystery and self-discovery. Written in the first person, we quickly get attached to Nico as we follow her through her darkest moments. The reader shares in her empowerment when Nico realizes that ultimately we can choose to take control of our emotional state: “There is comfort in being sad. But I am ready to give it up.” She learns to be a participant in life, rather than a mere victim of circumstance.""" ;
