    ns2:datePublished "1963"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This simple story relates little Swimmy’s narrow escape from a hungry tuna, and his lone journey through ocean waters, where he meets other creatures, such as a jellyfish, a lobster and an eel.\r
Colourful illustrations using ink-stamp effects create an artful and textural underwater world. The pinks and blues of the jellyfish mingle to fading purples, as its tentacles reach down the page. A seaweed forest seems to be stamped from lace. Through all these wonders, tiny Swimmy can be found, a plain black fish with a wide, bright eye. Readers may be inspired to create their own stamp-effect scenes.\r
Poetic language, such as “an eel whose tail was almost too far away to remember,” turns practical when Swimmy finally meets others of his kind, also hiding from all the predators: “‘you can’t just lie there,’ said Swimmy. ‘We must THINK of something.’”\r
The power of community and resourceful thinking is the final message of this gentle fable. Swimmy and his new friends learn to swim in fish-shaped formation, so they are free to explore: “they swam in the cool morning water and in the midday sun and chased the big fish away.”""" ;
