    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Each page features a different saying about the weather, from commonly heard expressions, such as “Red sky at night, sailor’s delight,” to the lesser known “Yellow streaks in a sunset sky, wind and daylong rain are nigh.” The stunning illustrations are photographs of paper dioramas, a technique that results in vibrant, magical scenes. The first shows a grandparent with two young grandchildren standing at a window, peering out at a blazing red sunset. Inside, the lifelike objects have a 3D quality. A woodstove gleams, a cuckoo clock hangs on the wall and the floorboards seem to creak underfoot. One two-page spread shows a humpback whale and a school of fish underwater surrounded by swaths of lavender and turquoise, while above the surface a red boat glides between enchanting hills. \r
At the end of the book, each saying is revisited and its origin explained: “When ladybugs swarm, expect a day that’s warm. True. Ladybugs will only fly in warm weather . . . they collect heat under their shells and release it by flying.” Some of the sayings are true but only in temperate zones, and some are deemed questionable: “Frogs will call before the rain, but in the sun are quiet again.” The text suggests that “the croaks sound louder because sound travels better in humid air.” Readers will linger over the majestic illustrations and come away with a deeper understanding of weather patterns as well as a collection of new sayings.""" ;
