    ns2:reviewBody """Deceptively simple, and perfect for read-aloud or paired reading, this book offers a good introduction to gardening while simultaneously teaching children to count from one to ten, and by tens to 100.\r
A bold cover and luminous cartoon-like illustrations of critters and plants spanning two pages are saturated with eye-catching colours that will engage younger children. Minimal text employing repetitive language patterns will also teach adjectives, colours and size. Two pages at the end of the book invite children to examine the inside of watermelons, pumpkins, eggplants, strawberries and other produce that Max and his sister Josephine harvest in their garden. The last page asks children to search for the various insects and birds scattered throughout the pages, including a bee, ladybug, robin and hummingbird.\r
