    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Central Avenue"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Calvin Sinclair’s family has moved to the country and Cal, who’s about to start sixth grade, only has his little brother for company. At six, Sammy idolizes his older brother, and Cal invents a series of task levels for him—from ant to eagle—each one increasingly complicated and often absurd. That summer, Cal meets Aleta and pushes his little brother away. When Sammy is diagnosed with acute myeloid leukemia, Cal feels guilty, unsure of his place in the family and his role as a big brother. In the hospital, he meets Oliver, a Mennonite boy who has been on the ward for over 600 days. Oliver is battling his own demons but acts as a kind of guide to navigating terminal illness (“‘We’re all dying—you’re dying, Dr. Parker’s dying, my mom’s dying—some of us are just a little faster than others’”). As his parents fall apart, Cal relies on Oliver and Aleta and learns how he can help soothe Sammy as the little boy slips away.\r
The novel includes practical advice for supporting patients and their families facing terminal illness. It features many survivor behaviours, including marital discord, guilt and self-blame. Sammy’s death is revealed from the outset; the novel does not rely on suspense, nor does it provide false hope. The extensive dialogue showcases characters dealing with the central theme of pediatric cancer, though the tender intimacy between Cal and Aleta is well developed. The book concludes with discussion questions for readers and educators as well as an interview with the author, who based the story on his work in pediatric oncology.""" ;
