    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This fun picture book riffs on well-known nursery rhymes to explore rhythm as a little monkey gets up in the morning. The story’s main structure is a reworking of “Down, Down Baby.” A “sleepy little monkey won’t get out of bed,” so “Mama called the Doctor,” though the doctor’s response is rather sillier than the popular tune, including a prescription for gooseberry pie, rutabaga and “Sis! Boom! Bah!” What follows cleaves to the original: “First you get the rhythm of the head,” then the feet, hands, and so forth, and before long the monkey is more spunky than sleepy, and stomping, shaking, clapping, and ding-donging with enthusiasm. The use of repetition and onomatopoeia creates a sing-song lilt, with momentum that builds as the movements accumulate and the energy rises. \r
\r
The illustrations are textured and compelling, with brightly coloured animals, especially the titular monkey, who jumps in puddles, shakes maracas, and finally bounces high in the air, tossing off an inexplicable sombrero as a bear, bunny, and dog gather round. The drawings are hand-created washes and acrylics that are then rendered digitally. Most of the illustrations are two-page spreads, then the book flips horizontally, which highlights the little monkey’s growing exuberance. The monkey is playfully anthropomorphized, with jean shorts and a T-shirt, rainboots, and a raincoat, and is relatable to young readers both at the sleepy start and as things get more rambunctious.""" ;
