    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Following a prefatory note that offers basic political and historical context, the book introduces readers to Canadians who have made history. Featured among many others are Jacques Cartier and Roberta Bondar (field of exploration), Elizabeth Arden (business), the Group of Seven (arts), Louis Riel (government), Emily Stowe (technology) and Wayne Gretzky and Silken Laumann (sports). Tecumseh and Terry Fox fall under the heading of heroes.\r
Each half-page biography lists the person’s roles and contributions, and details of his or her life. Quotes and trivia are provided as asides: on John Franklin’s last exploration journey, his ship was stocked not only with food, rum and tobacco, but also with 2,000 books. A list of Canadian Nobel laureates is provided, as well as a miscellaneous chapter of shorter introductions to figures such as Margaret Atwood, Michael J. Fox and Grey Owl.\r
Over 120 biographies are illustrated with representative colour drawings, showing busts and a few full-body pictures, and some framed and spot illustrations. Background detail offers appropriate visual context: Marc Garneau poses in front of a shuttle launch pad, while Canada’s first woman senator, Cairine Wilson, is shown in formal robes. Many Canadians are represented by pencil reproductions of Canada Post stamps issued in their honour.\r
An appended timeline traces Canadian accomplishments from the fifteenth century to the formation of Nunavut in 1999.""" ;
