    ns2:datePublished "2007"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Jeremy’s friend Sam loves math, while Jeremy can do without it. The “mathnik” and the math-not react differently when math is cut entirely out of their school curriculum. The “rumble” that ensues—should math be brought back and why?—begins by touching on basic notions like integers, rational numbers and imaginary numbers, before moving on to palindromes, Fibonacci sequences, logarithms and midi technology.\r
Insets titled “Jeremy Wrestles with the Weird Stuff” allows the protagonist to ask questions and offer explanations. Others feature biographies of mathematicians like Muhammad Ibn Musa Al-Khwarizmi and Srinivasa Ramanujan and examples of applied mathematics. Short tidbits offer overviews of notions such as exponential growth, math games or honeybee geometry.\r
The graphic presentation of the book relegates the text-heavy narrative to a pretext, with goofy representations of Jeremy and Sam and their classmates and teachers. The bright inset boxes feature cartoonish fonts, speech bubbles, and colourful illustrations. The representations of the various math concepts are visually compelling—Pascal’s triangle, with its looping arrows and boxed numbers, looks more like a game than an arrangement of binomial coefficients—though in many cases some pre-existing understanding is key to their enjoyment and comprehension.\r
The book concludes with a glossary, a bibliography and suggestions for further reading.""" ;
    ns2:title "Great Number Rumble: A Story of Math in Surprising Places" ;
