    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "HarperCollins Children’s Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book takes a sweet, straightforward look at how to find the right pet. A series of questions determine suitability and need: “Do you like big animals or small?” Other criteria include personality, like being cuddly; behaviour, like slithering or crawling up the wall; habitat, like living outside; and even size: “even one to ride!” The book also discusses the benefits of having a pet as a best friend, like trust and companionship. The girl in the book ends up finding her own perfect pet—“This turtle!” The tone is calm and soothing, and the girl encourages readers not to rush into a relationship with a pet, but rather to wait until the magic moment: “It will know. And you will know.” \r
Created in acrylic paint on wood and pencil, the illustrations are inviting and friendly. The girl has big eyes behind round glasses, and her simple features convey the emotional response the author is trying to evoke in readers. Aside from the turtle, the animals are never named, but rather the images fill in the narrative (the question, “do you need fun tricks?” is illustrated with a hamster turning in an exercise wheel, for instance, while an animal to hold when there’s a loud noise or when you’re feeling badly is a cat). Some of the animals are silly suggestions for pets, like a sheep or a ladybug, but the book’s emphasis is on being aware of your own needs and taking the time to know yourself.""" ;
