    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Life as a photojournalist in conflict zones is “exciting … but it is also soul-destroying to earn a living from photographing misery and devastation.” The author tells of her mission—“to change the world” by encouraging people to get involved—using photos of people and reality to tell the stories of children in Tunisia, Chad, Syria, Pakistan and many other war-torn countries.\r
Formatted like a scrapbook, sections correspond to the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child. “The Right to a Name and Nationality” looks at home and displacement, while “The Right to Affection, Love, and Understanding” examines how families are negatively impacted by war.\r
Each chapter includes “The Photographer’s Perspective,” in which the author brings attention to difficult issues like child labour, land mines and genocide. There are also case studies of initiatives toward peace or the well-being of children.\r
Presented with sensitivity and compassion, both the varied text and glossy photos are simple, clear and hard-hitting. One photo shows a brightly clad girl from Iraq, walking past a broken, rusted tank: “Children collect scrap metal to sell and play in burned-out military vehicles, which can be highly radioactive.” A boy holds a soccer ball made “from scrap plastic tied tightly with crisscrossed string.”\r
This is an important introduction to the realities and resilience of those living with war.""" ;
