    ns2:datePublished "1967"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """As winter approaches, a family of field mice work day and night to gather corn, nuts, wheat and straw for the cold, grey days ahead. All of them, that is, except Frederick, who sits by himself on a rock gathering colours and words and the sun’s rays. The others reproach him for not doing his share, but in an unexpected twist, his “supplies” are precisely what brings them comfort and warmth when their food runs out.\r
Written as a fable, the story combines simple text with repetitive elements to reinforce the idea that the hardworking mice resent Frederick’s “laziness” regarding the winter preparations. Three times they ask him why he doesn’t work. Three times he responds that what he does is, in fact, work: “. . . I am gathering words. For the winter days are long and many, and we’ll run out of things to say.”\r
In the double page collaged illustrations, the earthy palette changes with the seasons: summer greens becoming harvest shades and then greys for winter. When Frederick finally dazzles the cold, starved mice with his poetry, their hideout lights up with colour.\r
The simple text carries a powerful message about the value of nurturing the arts for the survival and happiness of the collective.""" ;
