ns2:Bookdeafb05d-6ff6-4eba-abbb-85d28403f5c5 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "John Lewis" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53603" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Top Shelf Productions"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This graphic memoir is the second in the trilogy on Congressman John Lewis and the US civil rights movement in the 1960s. In this book, John solidifies his role with the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC), as the nation’s attention is drawn by their anti-segregation sit-ins and protests for black voter registration in the South. While the activists gain momentum, so does a racist backlash, including bombings, imprisonment and the murder of children.\r
Major thinkers such as Stokely Carmichael, Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X are introduced, as are lesser known figures such as the venerable A. Philip Randolph (labour leader under President Roosevelt) and the “devout pacifist and brilliant organizer,” Bayard Rustin.\r
The plot conveys the strength and bravery of an oppressed people—and the outraged reactions of those of privilege. Meanwhile, concise narrative and lively dialogue relate activists’ determination, intelligence and wit. “‘Deputy Tyson, do you mean anything derogatory when you call us boy?’ ‘Don’t know nothin’ ‘bout no ‘rogatory. All I know is if you boys don’t stop that singin’, y’all gon’ be singin’ in the rain.’”\r
High-contrast monochrome images in this graphic text reflect the inherent drama of the story. One panel depicts prison guards dragging a fire hose toward cell bars. Subsequent images show gushing water blasting a prisoner’s face. Panels grow bright at the march on Washington DC, as John speaks to the crowd: “‘Wake up, America!’ ‘WAKE UP!! For we cannot stop … cannot be patient.”""" ;
