ns2:Bookdf3b803c-c1e7-4cf9-82a6-14c00127260e a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Joanne Liu" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56302" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Prestel Verlag – Verlagsgruppe Random House"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A little child’s discovery of an art museum hinges on everything but the art in this wordless picture book about paying close attention. Max wanders around a museum, but instead of looking at the art he notices his surroundings, peering up at visitors, rushing to a picture window to delight in sun-dappled leaves after completely overlooking a large impressionist painting, greeting a cleaner as others snap photos of marble statuary, ogling elaborate tattoos that look not unlike the ceramic their bearer is admiring.… Rather than trying to instill codified principles of fine-art appreciation, this book prioritizes and celebrates a child’s instinct for examining bugs, climbing on furniture and interacting rather than looking for meaning. The sense of wonder extends beyond the gallery walls as well, as Max points out the sunset to his mother on their walk home. \r
\r
The museum features art from most major Western art collections, such as Rothko, Miró, Vermeer or Matisse; it is sufficiently recognizable that readers young and old may have some degree of familiarity with it. The museum itself is typical, with a diverse population of visitors, many of whom can lead to interesting observations and discussions (a pregnant woman, a man and his granddaughter being silly, furrowed-browed patrons contemplating a Guernica-style mural). The densely coloured, painted illustrations that carry the narrative make it more compelling for readers to see what Max is up to now: for instance, as adults examine a Henry Moore sculpture, Max peeks through one of the holes at an equally delighted baby on the other side.""" ;
