    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Seventeen-year-old Seth is dumped, fired from his part-time job and learns his father may be having an affair—all in the same afternoon. Creating a podcast gives him an outlet for analyzing his break-up and the possible breakdown of his family. Over an eventful summer, Seth embarks on a journey towards self-discovery that includes the exploration of the nature of relationships.\r
Using a podcast for self-expression creates a strong literary structure for this funny tale of emotional turmoil. Seth’s podcasts also provide reflective pauses among his real-life adventures. “Someone’s got to hear about what happened tonight, and I sure as hell can’t tell anyone I actually know.”\r
Light and humorous language delivers insight into relationship dynamics, both healthy and not. Over time, characters’ true colours emerge with subtlety and sophistication. Seth’s podcasts incorporate scientific concepts such as sexual selection (“Antlers bigger than chandeliers don’t lend themselves to survival; they lend themselves to getting some hot elk bootie”) and human chemistry (“Years ago, he met my mother and the dopamine and norepinephrine dumped into his brain”). The idea of mapping and containing love appeals to the wounded Seth. Yet his relationships with new girls, his father and the “other woman,” testify to love’s more mysterious aspects. A dramatic father-son tournament at the golf club weaves all these threads together into a satisfying finish.""" ;
