    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Two children are staying with their grandparents for six days. It rains for the first three days, so the protagonist and her brother explore “the big old house” and play dress-up. Her grandfather promises to explain where the rain comes from once the storm passes. On the fourth day, “patches of sunlight appeared on the kitchen floor,” so they venture outside to look for the biggest puddle in the world.\r
Rich, textured illustrations, in traditional and digital watercolours, fill the page with contrast and energy. One two-page spread shows the kids outside with their grandfather and the dog. Light and dark greens, yellows and browns build a layered scene of bushes, trees, grass and flowers. The text embodies a childlike enthusiasm and features poetic descriptions: “Wild flowers had opened in the rain. Bees crawled inside them like little balls of buzz.” The grandfather drips water onto a rock to illustrate evaporation: “The water in the air becomes the clouds in the sky.” They follow a river until they discover “the ocean—the biggest puddle in the world!”\r
\r
That night, the rain returns, and the girl is happy with the knowledge that she and her family, along with “the rain and the puddles and the pond and the ocean,” are “all connected . . . in a wonderful way.” The final illustration shows the girl smiling in bed, whispering to her brother who is “already dreaming.” This energetic story reinforces children’s joyful curiosity and the ways in which we are all connected.""" ;
