    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Cormorant_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Everyone disappoints you eventually.” Everyone leaves in the end: Serena’s closest confidant, her brother Devin, who had been struggling with drug addiction, has disappeared. Her parents, numbed by grief, leave Serena to cope on her own.\r
This novel is anchored by Serena’s authentic first-person voice. She wrestles with the contradictions of being fifteen: “I can cry and lust at the same time.” She can hate her body and love it, hate her family and need them. Underneath everything, the fear of getting hurt spills from home to school and to weekend parties. When Serena’s boyfriend tries to bully her into a humiliating sexual show, she leaves him and swears off dating.\r
Secretly, however, Serena is proud of recently losing thirty pounds and she loves the new attention she attracts. She finds it hard to resist the dreamy customer she meets at work. Gage is 19 and far more mature than the unromantic, uncouth jocks at her school. He acts like a gentleman and is a good father to his young daughter.\r
Serena learns to deal with family issues, relationship challenges and her own self-image. She comes to terms with judging people based on how they look and learns that she must stop doing it to herself. “Maybe being a better version of myself means caring less about all of them and how they see me,” she realizes.""" ;
    ns2:title "Sweetest Thing You Can Sing" ;
