ns2:Booke519c7fa-7af9-4e87-bb13-8c91b6ce671d a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Katherine Lawrence" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55039" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Coteau_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Millie’s greatest preoccupation is that she wants a dog, at least until her parents announce that they’re separating. Her adoption of Rhuby, from a Cree woman, keeps her busy, increases her sense of responsibility, and keeps her mind off the family crisis. Her mother is having an affair, and her father has moved out, into an apartment that doesn’t allow dogs. Although she misses Rhuby, that does give Millie “a break from cleaning up dog poop”. When the unhoped-for happens and her father comes home, it’s only to announce that he has cancer. \r
\r
Through it all, Millie turns, as she always has, to her lost twin brother Billy. Billy died before they were born, and his memory serves as a sounding board. As the interlocutor for this diary written in verse, Billy is both absent and tangible—Millie speaks of them as a plural: “we’re eleven going on twelve next month.” \r
\r
The series of poems that make up Millie’s diary are in lyric narrative verse, with dialogue and material from text messages woven in. The first-person voice is tweeny, as when Millie whines, slams doors, and kicks her sister in the poem “Not Fair.” The poems filter Millie’s emotions through figurative devices that allow her some emotional distance. For instance, Millie writes to Billy as a “weather girl” reporting “from the latest family squall,” going on to develop the association with “yells of thunder from Dad, lightning in Mum’s voice;” the poem “Playing Baseball” compares Millie’s sudden loss of family security to a ball game—“I thought I was home safe” and the conceit in the poem “Hold With Two Hands” is that picking a puppy is like picking an ice-cream flavour “Strawberry pink tongues, cocoa eyes.”""" ;
