    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Houghton_Mifflin_Harcourt ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Annie is the new girl, rebellious and beautiful. Jessie is a social outcast with anxiety disorder and an overprotective mom. They become best friends, but Jessie worries that Annie will ditch her and join the school’s popular mean girls. She’s right—that’s exactly what happens. But the reasons are complex. Annie, for all her outward confidence, is desperately needy, grieving her dead mother.\r
 \r
Told by the two girls in alternating chapters, the story is fast-paced, with lots of dialogue and an engaging teenage tone. “I can’t get last night out of my brain. I feel like puking every time I think about it, but no matter what I do, the horrifying scenes keep playing over and over again in my mind.” The ups and downs of their friendship are thick with bullying and shunning led by mean-girl Courtney, who has targeted Jessie for the past three years.\r
 \r
Jessie struggles with other issues, including her need for Ativan, (“I have only three more pills left. Three more days of comfort.”) while Annie gets pregnant and her stepmother pushes her to have an abortion. “No one notices that I’m no longer a living person ...” Annie thinks when it’s over.\r
 \r
Despite all these girls have to face, the story ends happily. Annie becomes more self-aware and Jessie blossoms, standing up to both her mother and Courtney. She even begins her first romance. Jessie and Annie resume their friendship. And it, too, is stronger than before.""" ;
