ns2:Booke74e12be-562f-4078-b209-2ee56f73b5c3 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Adam Lehrhaupt" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56301" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Paula Wiseman – Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book playfully details the idea-generation process for storytelling or writing. The unseen first-person narrator introduces readers to their teacher’s idea jar, which is full of all kinds of words to help get a story started. The themes are sometimes simple (a robot) and sometimes more complex (a horseless cowgirl), while some ideas can put two words together, even mixing parts of speech, to see what happens (for instance, “giant” and “dragon”). Once an idea has been selected, “there are tons of ways to make a story”—orally, in writing, visually, or collaboratively. As various children choose and develop stories, a Viking who has escaped from the idea jar pesters them to make their stories about him—a reminder that “it’s important to create stories for your ideas, or else your ideas get rowdy.” The Viking eventually tips over the idea jar, and all the ideas, from the cowgirl to a pirate, some animals and a blue monster, come tumbling out, stampeding around the classroom until the teacher restores order by encouraging his pupils and the readers to create a story for the ideas running amok. The book ultimately seems to encourage a balance between imaginative freedom and creative control. \r
\r
The gouache, pen and ink illustrations are silly and creative. The children and the idea-jar creatures are the same size and style, suggesting a cohabitation that will ring true for young readers. The drawings are simple, with a childlike aesthetic. The Viking is especially expressive, from his boredom as he sulks cross-legged, his spear and shield tossed to the side, to his exultation as the rowdiness begins. The idea-characters speak in colourful, cartoonish speech bubbles, and some of the warning words (“DUCK,” “HIDE,” “RUN!”) as things get boisterous are written in appropriately tall and bright letters.""" ;
