ns2:Booked382b1e-c7d6-4cbd-983c-108f76e48490 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Caron Levis" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53792" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Based on the true story of Gus and Ida, two polar bears who lived in the Central Park Zoo in New York, this tale of loss is a beautiful tribute to what it means to love and to grieve. The two polar bears loved to play together or flop on their favourite rock, never without one the other. When Gus understands that Ida is dying, he does his best to make her comfortable, but finally has to let his best friend go. Remembering the words of his beloved, “you don’t have to see it to feel it,” he looks up at the sky and sees an Ida-shaped cloud and knows she is near, always.
Told with compassion and heart, the text is lovely and poetic. “Then one sunny day, while Gus smoothed her fur; Ida curled into quiet, her eyes fluttered shut, and they didn’t open anymore. Gus pressed one last pat into Ida’s paw.” Just the right number of words per page drive the story forward, as this highly emotional tale builds in small heart-wrenching increments.
Gorgeous, full-bleed, digitally rendered illustrations have a soft touch and simplicity to their powerful imagery. Depicted in their habitat, offset by the New York City skyline, the bears’ postures and gestures of intimacy and friendship speak louder than any words.
An author’s note adds context to this moving story.""" ;
