ns2:Bookedd28fdb-ff7c-45fb-8a72-9da1f8b5285a a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andrew Larsen" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56480" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book features a pair of siblings, the older of whom encourages the younger to write a story using the tools and knowledge at his disposal. The book is written in the first-person voice of the little brother, who knows letters, “but I don’t know many words.” He’s envious of his older sister, because she can write stories, but she points out that “every story starts with a single word, and every word starts with a single letter.” After breaking down the process of writing into manageable steps, she describes the process of creating a story: the beginning, the setting, the middle, the plot and the end, though she defines each step without naming it. The letters and letter-like squiggles the little boy traces take on a life of their own, as when a series of Vs become shark fins. The next day at school, the little boy proudly shows his story to his teacher Mrs. Singh and his classmates, who help him think about his story’s ending and brainstorm their own stories. The book empowers even preschoolers to tap into their narrative creativity and helps them see their sometimes seemingly slow language acquisition as full of potential, no matter what stage they’re at. \r
\r
The illustrations depict a plausibly supportive and complex relationship between two young siblings—the frustrations and envy of the little brother, the encouragement and maturity of the more capable older sister. The actual story is depicted in the drawings, and the little boy’s squiggles and preliterate attempts at writing letters are realistic representations of preschoolers’ language and calligraphy, which will be relatable to young readers and writers. The digitally created images are structured in panels and with speech bubbles, like a graphic novel, further lending a grown-up aspect to early language acquisition, reading and creative writing. \r
\r
The story is continued in a sequel, Another Squiggly Story.""" ;
