    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Boom! Studios"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Goldie Vance would love to be the house detective at the resort her father manages but, for now, the teen must settle for returning wandering toddlers to their worried parents. When a priceless jewel necklace is stolen from a guest, Goldie attaches herself to the investigation of the hapless house detective. She quickly deduces that her fellow ice-cream scooper, Rob, stole the necklace and lost it after gambling on a drag race. Goldie, who also parks cars at the resort, borrows a Mustang to challenge the other race winner and wins the necklace back. When the necklace turns out to be a fake and its German rocket-scientist owner goes missing, Goldie, with her friend Cheryl and her crush Diane, tackles a more complicated mystery, with forays into a childhood grudge, Russian involvement and a space colony on Mars.\r
The characters are extensively developed: Goldie is a bi-racial, lesbian daughter of divorced parents, with a knack for detective work, car racing and hot-wiring; her mother works as a mermaid in an underwater bar show; Cheryl is training to be an astronaut and dating the ice-cream-jockey necklace thief. The plot twists are dizzying, in line with the energy of the main character and the pace of this kid-detective genre.\r
The graphic art accurately represents the demographics of the luxury hotel business, including racial imbalances in a southern Florida that feels old-fashioned. The characters are drawn as wide-eyed, clean-cut kids and the background and interactions are reminiscent of other crime-caper characters and vintage Americana.""" ;
