ns2:Bookf4fee901-e09b-4092-ae70-2cddbe6682f4 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Dennis Lee" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53201" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2000"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This book contains all the ingredients to delight readers and hook children on poetry: rhyme, repetition, silly topics, fun diction and just enough nonsense. Consider “Flying”: “Fly me round the microwave,Fly me round the moon.Fly me like a millionaireOn a Saturday afternoon!”\r
Every line is carefully metered, but each word earns its keep. Thematically, the range is wide—from going to the movies to the smell of flowers in the garden, from a bully to a dream horse. Nor do the poems shy away from darker topics (“Dead men in Edmonton” we learn, “Lie very still”), though the reader is always treated as an intelligent, literate interlocutor.\r
The full-page and spot illustrations are fantastical: “The Bully” shows a boy perched on a dragon; in “The Movies”, a large bug is weeping in the second row. Poetry is embedded in the drawings—on the side of a table, amid tree branches or in the hollow of a rolling garbage can—and even throughout the front matter (a wavy line of text on the ISBN page, led by a row of dancing insects, reads, “Bless my booty, Bless my soul— Here comes brattyBug patrol!”)\r
A collection of poetry that truly honours the spirit of childhood.""" ;
    ns2:title "Bubblegum Delicious" ;
