ns2:Bookf57437e9-84f1-481e-bb94-ef93805e3c79 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Catherine Leblanc" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53270" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Insight"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Afraid of ghosts? Fear no more. Ghosts may slam doors, float through walls, make unsettling noises or interfere with homework, but this whimsical how-to guide, with its quirky strategies for beating ghosts at their own game, might chase away the pesky creatures for good. The only catch: you may regret it. Ghosts “take with them many mysteries and dreams. And at night, no one will be there to tickle your feet!”\r
Told in a playful tone, with language that is conversational and packed with mischievous ideas, this very readable volume turns potential fears into empowering strategies for overcoming them: “If a gang of little ghosts dumps all your sister’s junk in your room, don’t take the blame. Say it wasn’t you!”\r
The watercolour and ink illustrations combine the humorous with the grotesque. A dark purple palette pervades the pages. Cartoon style illustrations depict ghosts as white floating creatures with large worried eyes, grimacing mouths and flailing arms. Children are devious in their victories, with pointed eyebrows and triumphant grins.\r
Part of a lighthearted how-to series on various frights, children are the heroes here, taking charge of their anxiety through action. The book closes with an illustration of a brother and sister building a large patchwork effigy of a ghost, spooking all the real ones away.""" ;
