    ns2:datePublished "1990"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Fitzhenry___Whiteside ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Brief chapters, large type and plenty of sub-headings help deliver key facts about the settlement of New France—from its founding by Champlain to the battle of the Plains of Abraham. Readers learn about missionary Jesuits, coureurs de bois, settlers, and some information about First Nations peoples who both welcomed and warred with them.\r
Adventures of historic figures such as Jean de Brebeuf (“The Giant Black Robe”) and Marie La Tour (“Battle for Acadia”) are recounted in simple yet dramatic terms. General conditions and social history are related in sections such as “Young Bride,” “Well-fed Colonists” and “Seigneurial System.”\r
Detailed black and white illustrations show the lands, forts, fashions, weapons and tools of the time. Maps and charts provide informational graphics. Most chapters offer a related activity, such as a crossword puzzle, cut-out models and colouring pages. An index and answer key complete the back material, while an engaging introduction discusses misadventures and misunderstandings of early European explorers.""" ;
