    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simply_Read_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Kate insists on accompanying her older sister and father to the sugar shack. She tries to help by emptying a pail full of sap but it’s too heavy and she spills the whole thing. She waves her mitten in the steam coming off the boiling sap and drops it into the evaporator. She tries to find sticks for the fire but gets lost in the woods. Kate can’t seem to do anything right until her father needs Popsicle sticks for the taffy and she remembers she has some in her pocket. Kate carefully pours the hot syrup on the snow and winds the sticks all by herself.\r
Taffy Time is a family story about being too small to help but learning to contribute in small, symbolic ways. The sugar shack setting allows a glance at the process of making maple syrup and pouring taffy. Kate’s father patiently explains the boiling process: “The evaporator warms the sap and boils the water out of it so that it can turn into sticky syrup.”\r
The watercolour illustrations have a 2-dimensional collage feel. Objects are made of simple shapes with solid colours and almost no texture. Kate’s coat, for example, is a pink rectangle with black buttons, her legs are thick grey lines. The minimalistic drawings match the simple text to create a charming portrait of springtime on Sugar Hill Farm. Kate is still young but she is learning to participate in her family’s maple syrup business. And enjoying the delicious final product proves to be no problem at all.""" ;
