    ns2:datePublished "1989"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this stylishly written story, Mei Mei is a smart, headstrong girl from Hong Kong, who resents moving to New York City.\r
“In Chinese” and “In English” become opposing refrains, as the story recounts the pros and cons of Mei Mei’s new life. The English language is seen from an outside perspective: “T-R-I-P, thought Mei Mei. The letters “T” and “R” bang against each other, and each keeps its own sound. Not like Chinese.”\r
Drawings of fluid line and watercolour fills depict Mei Mei’s ‘foreign’ classroom, and her beloved Chinese community centre. As she learns English words that have no Chinese equivalent, Mei Mei grasps her head tearfully. In another image, she flails from a nightmare: “Yee Fong said, ‘Who are you?’ in English . . . She woke up shouting, ‘I am Mei Mei!’ in Chinese.”\r
In the end, a long walk—and lots of talk—with ESL tutor Nancy helps Mei Mei overcome fears about loss of identity. “They both laughed so hard, neither one could say a word in English or Chinese.” This is a great read for newcomers learning English and for the rest of us who welcome them.""" ;
