    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Can you hear the sounds of our world? The accompanying artwork shows a cluster of motley houses, with mothers of different ethnicities kissing their children awake in each window. Nearby, a soaring seabird chants, Listen! Listen! Listen!\r
The pages that follow feature full-spread illustrations of a variety of animals. The style is simple but playful, with an earthy palette of greens and browns accented with bold fuchsia. Pencil shading gives the drawings an unpolished aesthetic. The animals’ sounds are rendered in large, colourful lettering. “Hiss! Hiss! Hiss!” says a Gila monster. “Snap! Snap! Snap!” go a trio of crocodiles. Some of the illustrations are vertical instead of horizontal.\r
The rhythmic texts on each page follow a pattern, describing habitat features, the animal’s action and the place that animal calls home, all in two sentences: “Around a giant kapok tree, bright parrots flit and fly. The rainforest is their world.” Throughout the book, the author uses unique action verbs: crocodiles “glide,” penguins “waddle,” monkeys “swing” and eagles “soar.”\r
The mother tucks her children into bed, reassuring them that “all is well in our world.” The last two pages include a list of all the animals in the book along with a more detailed description of each animal, including its unique features and habitat.""" ;
